 for the whole of the United Kingdom are not available. Justice is devolved in Scotland and Northern Ireland and those statistics are matters for the devolved administrations.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","105374","2017-10-09T08:30:59.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760938/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760938/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Young Offenders: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people under the age of 18 were convicted of a criminal offence in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016 in the UK.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760939","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government will be considering carefully all the recommendations made by David Lammy in his report on the treatment and outcomes for BAME individuals in the criminal justice system and will respond in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-09T08:29:55.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760939/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760939/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Young Offenders: Criminal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he will implement the recommendations of the Carlile and Lammy reviews to seal youth criminal records.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760940","Leader of the House","false","2017-10-09","<p>The additional UK Government financial support for Northern Ireland will be treated in line with other Government spending commitments.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-10-09T10:09:03.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760940/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760940/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-09-14","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of establishing a separate procedure for the House's scrutiny of and agreement to the funding on the £1billion of additional financial support for Northern Ireland referred to in the agreement between the Government and the DUP, published on 26 June 2017; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","105415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760941","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>As I stated in response to Question 7353, the Scotland-Malawi Partnership has raised the issue of visas for Malawians to the UK with officials in the Scotland Office, Home Office and UK Visas and Immigration (UKVI).</p><p> </p><p>Officials have explored with the Scotland-Malawi Partnership how to support the preparation of visa applications. I understand that provision has been made within the Home Office/UKVI to support the ongoing relationship with the Scotland-Malawi Partnership.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-09T14:29:47.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760941/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760941/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-14","Visas: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7353 on visas: Malawi, if he will make representations to the Home Secretary to request that she review the (a) efficacy of procedures and (d) adequacy of the time taken to process Visit visas for Malawians who wish to travel to Scotland.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","105393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760942","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>My Department receives a large number of requests for the ministerial team and officials to meet with stakeholders to discuss a variety of issues on a regular basis and each invitation is considered on a case by case basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","105390","2017-10-09T14:31:06.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760942/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760942/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-14","Citizens Advice Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8081, on what date he will next meet with representatives of Citizens Advice Scotland.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","105392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760943","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>My Department receives a large number of requests for the ministerial team and officials to meet with stakeholders to discuss a variety of issues on a regular basis and each invitation is considered on a case by case basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","105392","2017-10-09T14:31:06.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760943/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760943/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-14","Women against State Pension Inequality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8090, on what date he will next meet with representatives of the Women Against State Pension Inequality campaign.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","105390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760944","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Train Service Specification is part of the Franchise Agreement and will see a recasting of the South Western timetables, in December 2018 and December 2020. December 2018 will see the introduction of the modified fleet of Class 442 trains on the Portsmouth Direct services between London Waterloo and Portsmouth Harbour. While the contracted maximum journey times for off-peak services to both Portsmouth Harbour and Southampton Central are consistent with current fastest journey times, we are expecting to see journey time improvements arising from the December 2018 Timetable re-cast. South Western Railway, will be carrying out consultation with Stakeholders on the December 2018 timetable in the coming months.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-12T11:44:39.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760944/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760944/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","South Western Rail Franchise: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what obligations and timescales he has placed on the new South Western Railway under its franchise agreement on the introduction of faster trains from London Waterloo to (a) Portsmouth and (b) Southampton.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Seely","Isle of Wight","Mr Bob Seely","105398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760945","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department for Transport has made no assessment of the scale and timing of any required infrastructure works on Ryde Pier, Isle of Wight</p><p> </p><p>The infrastructure on the Isle of Wight is owned by Network Rail and the responsibilities for maintenance and renewal of these assets is apportioned between Network Rail and the Train Operating Company (South Western Railway, SWR) under the terms of the lease between these organisations. This lease is due for renewal in 2019.</p><p> </p><p>The Department would expect Network Rail to make provision for any routine maintenance and renewal works required within their overall cost base for activities for Control Period 6 and to reflect these in the renewed lease.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-12T11:43:18.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760945/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760945/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Railways: Ryde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment (a) his Department and (b) Network rail have made on the scale and timing of any required infrastructure works on Ryde Pier, Isle of Wight, to ensure that there is no risk to the continued and long-term provision of rail services on that route; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Seely","Isle of Wight","Mr Bob Seely","105401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760946","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Information on contractor anticipated final cost (AFC) is detailed below. The proportion of Network Rail’s expenditure to be spent on engaging third party contractors in the current control period is approximately 69%.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contractor AFC (millions)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total CP5 Funding (millions)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CP5 Enhancements</strong></p></td><td><p>£13,224</p></td><td rowspan="3"><p><br> <br> £38.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CP5 Renewals</strong></p></td><td><p>£13,075</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total CP5 </strong></p></td><td><p>£26,299</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note that these figures are subject to a number of caveats. For example, it is not possible to pull out all materials costs, so these figures include some materials costs relating to renewals and enhancements, or may include other aspects such as Distribution Network Operator costs.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T14:10:57.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760946/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760946/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Network Rail: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of Network Rail's expenditure in the current control period is spent on engaging third party contractors, excluding materials and energy suppliers, for (a) renewables work and (b) enhancement projects.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","105353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760947","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The infrastructure on the Isle of Wight is owned by Network Rail and the responsibilities for maintenance and renewal of these assets is apportioned between Network Rail and the Train Operating Company (South Western Railway, SWR) under the terms of the lease between these organisations. This lease is due for renewal in 2019.</p><p> </p><p>We would expect Network Rail to make provision for any routine maintenance and renewal works required within their overall cost base for activities for Control Period 6 and to reflect these in the renewed lease. Ultimately, costs falling to Network Rail are borne by the public purse.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, South Western Railway are due to submit a costed option to the Secretary of State by the end of March 2018 in relation to the future operation of the Island Line. To the extent that this is acceptable, it may result in an adjustment to franchise payments made to Government by the franchisee. SWR are in the process of consulting with local stakeholders regarding options.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-12T11:52:42.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760947/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760947/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Railways: Ryde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the cost of necessary infrastructure works on the Ryde Pier rail route will be funded by Network Rail; and whether such funding will be borne by the (a) public purse and (b) franchise.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Seely","Isle of Wight","Mr Bob Seely","105395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760948","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>HS2 is the largest infrastructure project in Europe. Once complete it will connect eight out of our ten biggest cities, increasing rail capacity on the current system and reducing journey times, while also creating thousands of jobs and acting as a catalyst for economic growth across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd is the executive non-departmental public body established to develop and deliver the HS2 programme. The company is responsible for promotion, engagement and communication to those with an interest in the project.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Community Engagement department at HS2 Ltd, who work on Phases 1 and 2a, has responsibility to build positive working relationships with residents and their elected representatives, local authorities and businesses along the line of route during planning and delivery of the project. It employs 32 staff. Community engagement staff who work on the proposed Phase 2b route, sit under the Phase 2 department, and employ 49 staff.</p><p> </p><p>The Corporate Affairs department at HS2 Ltd exists to help the company build and maintain its reputation. It has responsibility for communications to audiences such as: the public, politicians, journalists, project stakeholders and internal staff. It employs 45 staff.</p><p> </p><p>Other HS2 Ltd departments engage statutory stakeholders as part of their role in planning, developing and delivering the project. This includes, but is not restricted to, discussions with local authority planning and policy teams.</p><p> </p><p>All figures as of 02 October 2017.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-12T11:37:39.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760948/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760948/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many members of staff of HS2 Ltd work on communications for that project.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760949","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The current proposal by the Welsh Government is that if ownership of the Cardiff Valley Lines is transferred, Network Rail will not remain responsible for their day-to-day maintenance and operation.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T14:08:39.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760949/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760949/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Network Rail will remain responsible for and have control of the day-to-day maintenance and operation of the Valley Lines after their transfer to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","105332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760950","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Following the proposed transfer of ownership of the Cardiff Valley Lines, allocation of responsibility for control of the day-to-day maintenance and operation of the Valley Lines would be a matter for the Welsh Government.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T14:25:57.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760950/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760950/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the successful private sector bidder for the (a) Wales and Borders and (b) Metro franchise will be responsible for and have control of the day-to-day maintenance and operation of the Valley Lines.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","105333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760952","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The data requested is not held, however the number of older workers in the UK is at a record high, currently standing at 9.9m workers aged 50 years and over. 4.2m women aged 50-64 are in employment; this compares to 3.5m five years ago. There are 1.2 million individuals in employment aged over 65, of which 39% are women.</p><p> </p><p>Employment rates for older workers have also been increasing and recently reached record highs. Since ten years ago, the employment rate has increased by 6.2 percentage points (pp) (from 64.9% to 71.1%) for people aged 50-64. The current employment rate for women aged 50-64 is at a record high of 66.8%.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on estimates of employment, unemployment, economic inactivity and other employment-related statistics for the UK can be found in the “UK labour market: September 2017” statistical bulletin published at the Office for National Statistics (ONS) website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/september2017" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/september2017</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to supporting people aged 50 years and over to remain in and return to work; the ‘Fuller Working Lives: A Partnership Approach’ strategy was published on 2nd February. This, crucially, is led by employers, but it also sets out the case for action by individuals, and the role of Government in supporting them in planning their careers and their approach to retirement. The Strategy and supporting evidence base are available at the attached web address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach</a></p><p> </p><p>Analysis on the headline measures that the government uses to monitor progress on Fuller Working Lives can be found in this statistical release:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/economic-labour-market-status-of-individuals-aged-50-and-over-trends-over-time-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/economic-labour-market-status-of-individuals-aged-50-and-over-trends-over-time-september-2017</a></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-10-09T16:55:57.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760952/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760952/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","State Retirement Pensions: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many women in Barnsley born in the 1950s and affected by the change in state pension age have returned to employment from a position of unemployment.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","105266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760954","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>My Department has no plans to collect or publish these data.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-09T17:21:28.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760954/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760954/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8092, on social security benefits: disqualification, if he will (a) collect the information requested and (b) analyse any information collected to determine whether there is a correlation between sanctions and food bank use; and if he will publish his findings.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","105394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760955","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>This information is commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p><p>However the Word document attached lists the jobcentres that are due to move their services to other sites and to close by 31 March 2018. Exact dates for these sites are still being agreed but closures will be through a phased approach.</p><p> </p><p>We are taking a phased approach to the closure of these Jobcentres because there are a significant number of activities that need to take place to move people, our customers and caseloads to the importing Jobcentre. In phasing this work in this way, we can minimise the risk of any disruption to vital services. For the vast majority of DWP offices there will be no change in location. Where we are closing a site, we will take all possible precautions to minimise disruption for customers.</p><p> </p><p>This will mean that the DWP will be able to offer a more efficient service, while delivering good value for the taxpayer and saving over £140 million a year for the next 10 years.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-11T15:42:08.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760955/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760955/answer","105377 list of jobcentres 9.10.17.docx","Jobcentres List","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760955/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many job centres will close to the public before the lease on their premises expires in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","105377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760956","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-09T16:38:00.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760956/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760956/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Jobseeker's Allowance: Criminal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people claiming jobseeker's allowance in (a) Ceredigion, (b) Wales and (c) the UK have a criminal record.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760957","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>Please find the response to your question in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Caseload</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average Age</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>1,020,020</p></td><td><p>74.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>10,001,160</p></td><td><p>74.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>647,330</p></td><td><p>74.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source: DWP Work and Pensions Longitudinal Study, February 2017.</em></p><p><em>Caseload figures have been rounded to the nearest 10.</em></p><p><em>Averages are means.</em></p><p> </p><p>There are additionally 430 persons resident in Great Britain whose location is unknown.</p><p>DWP does not administer State Pensions for Northern Ireland. The figures above relate solely to those that are administered by the DWP.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-10-09T17:09:48.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760957/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760957/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the (a) number and (b) average age was of state pension recipients in (i) Scotland, (ii) England, (iii) Wales and (iv) Northern Ireland in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","105262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760958","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>There is no data broken down by area or region. However, data published on 15 September 2017 shows that, nationally, in June 2017 76% of new Universal Credit households received their first payment in full and on time. Across the whole of Universal Credit 92% of all households received full payment on time. The published data can be found here.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-payment-timeliness-january-to-june-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-payment-timeliness-january-to-june-2017</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-11T15:47:44.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760958/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760958/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of universal credit claims was processed and paid within six weeks in the last six-month period for which figures are available in (a) Barnsley, (b) South Yorkshire and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","105265"
