"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760968","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government’s Clean Growth Strategy will be published shortly. This will set out our proposals for decarbonising the UK economy through the 2020s.</p><p>We have already made good progress on food waste collection, with 52% of local authorities in England providing food waste collections in 2015/16, either separate or mixed with garden waste. This is an increase from 27% in 2009. The Waste &amp; Resources Action Program (WRAP) has published guidance on increasing capture for food waste collection services and we encourage local authorities to take this into account when making decisions on services.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-09T16:31:51.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760968/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760968/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Food: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government has considered including in its Clean Growth Plan the provision of funding for local authorities to introduce separate food waste collections.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","105342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760969","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>No fines have been issued for non-compliance with the requirements to file people with significant control information (PSC) with Companies House.</p><p> </p><p>Compliance is Companies House’ primary aim, rather than prosecution. It is taking action to ensure that all companies on the active register report their PSC information.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:12:41.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760969/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760969/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many fines have been issued for non-compliance with the People with Significant Control register; and how much has been paid in such fines.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","105316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760970","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>Companies House's internal statistics indicate that 130,000 companies on its active register (around 3% of the total) have not yet provided information on their people with significant control.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:10:00.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760970/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760970/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of companies that have not complied with the terms of the People with Significant Control register.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","105317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760971","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>No action has been taken at this time against the promoters and officers of Magnolia Fundaction UK Ltd for filing inappropriate information in Italian at Companies House.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:06:43.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760971/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760971/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has taken any action against the promoters and officers of Magnolia Fundaction UK Ltd for filing information at Companies House which gave an officer's address as 00 Via Dei 40 Landroni, Ali Babba, Italy 00100.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760972","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government worked closely with the exhibition organiser, Clarion Defence and Security Ltd, to ensure that all exhibitors at Defence and Security Equipment International (DSEI) were aware of their export control obligations. This includes which items they were prohibited from supplying or delivering – or agreeing to supply or deliver – or refraining from acts calculated to promote the supply or delivery of such items, including exhibiting and advertising. Government hosted a pre-event briefing with Clarion to ensure they were fully aware of their responsibilities. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), who are responsible for the enforcement of export and trade controls, also attended the briefing to provide clear compliance guidance and to review the procedures Clarion had put in place.</p><p>The Export Control Joint Unit had a dedicated stand at DSEI which was manned by Ministry of Defence, Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Department for International Trade officials. HMRC were present during each day of the exhibition to ensure exhibitors complied with UK Trade Controls, as they were in 2015. C-RICH Co and other stall holders were visited by HMRC.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","105098","2017-10-12T11:57:27.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760972/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760972/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Arms Trade: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will take steps to monitor whether (a) C-RICH Co. Ltd and (b) other stall holders at the DSEI Arms Fair 2017 are (i) selling or (ii) promoting (A) electric stun guns baton type, (B) electric stun guns hand type, (C) leg irons and (D) thumb cuffs to countries which (1) the UK and (2) international obligations prohibit the sale of (aa) such equipment and (bb) military equipment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","105414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760973","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-10","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and other Ministers regularly meet with companies that invest in the UK, including on visits abroad, to the regions, and in London. This includes companies investing in regions across the whole of the UK, including Wales.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-10T09:57:22.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760973/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760973/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Foreign Investment in UK: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2017 to Question 9573, what discussions he has had with those EU companies which are investing most significantly in Wales after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","105359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760974","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department for International Trade is unable to release company specific information due to commercial sensitivities.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-12T12:11:58.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760974/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760974/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Foreign Investment in UK: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2017 to Question 9573, what the 10 biggest foreign inward investments from EU countries into Wales has been in each of the last 11 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","105358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760975","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>In line with the Conservative Manifesto, this Government is pressing for the rules that govern how, on whom, and for what purpose development assistance is spent to better reflect the breadth of our assistance around the world. The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development’s Development Assistance Committee (OECD-DAC) determines what may be counted as Official Development Assistance. As it operates by consensus, we are working with our DAC partners and other stakeholders to achieve this.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T16:06:24.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760975/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760975/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-14","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans she has to change OECD-DAC rules.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","105253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760976","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The British Government and the Government of Gibraltar are working to maintain and strengthen our economic links. Ministers discussed progress on this at the Joint Ministerial Council (Gibraltar Europe Negotiations) in September. The Treasury agreed to continue to work closely together with The Government of Gibraltar on financial services, committing to a programme of work on insurance. We have also established a working group to discuss mutual opportunities in the online gaming industry, where Gibraltar is a global leader.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-09T14:37:08.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760976/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760976/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-14","Free Trade: Gibraltar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to establish a free trade area between the UK and Gibraltar which will be in place after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","105405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760977","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government does not publish data detailing the value of defence exports broken down by individual country. However, export control licensing data broken down by country is published on gov.uk, and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data</a></p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-12T11:32:10.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760977/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760977/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Arms Trade: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will list the value of UK arms exports to each country in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","105378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760978","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-16","<p>Our discussions with India through our joint trade review have been wide-ranging and covered many aspects of our trading relationship. The review is principally an analytical project to understand our bilateral trading relationship, rather than a formal negotiation. As such, immigration rules have not been raised as a pre-requisite for further trade talks.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-16T10:19:54.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760978/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760978/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Trade Agreements: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2017 to Question 6797, whether India indicated during discussions on the trade relationship between the UK and India that the Government would have to relax immigration rules with India for a future trade deal to be agreed.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","105369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760979","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-10","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade met representatives of the following defence companies at DSEI 2017: Thales UK, MBDA and Leonardo.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-10T09:52:14.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760979/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760979/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Arms Trade: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with which arms dealers he has had discussions at the Defence and Security Equipment International Conference.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","105306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760980","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that we will bring about the end of the direct jurisdiction of the CJEU in the UK. After withdrawal, the UK will take back control of its laws. The Repeal Bill will end the supremacy of EU law. Our domestic law will once again be supreme. After we leave the EU, Parliament or, where appropriate, the devolved legislatures, will be free to change the law where they decide it is right to do so.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","10113","2017-10-09T15:02:21.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760980/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760980/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-14","Dispute Resolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to his Department's publication, Enforcement and dispute resolution-a future partnership paper, what his Department's definition is of direct jurisdiction.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","105328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/766950","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>Officials from DWP have met with a number of national and local organisations ahead of Universal Credit roll out.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent phase of expansion will only take the proportion of the forecast claimant population receiving UC from 8% currently to 10% by the end of January.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-09T16:27:11.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/766950/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/766950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/766950/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations his Department has received on the accelerated roll-out of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","901043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767779","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>We are investing an extra £1.4billion in children and young people’s mental health services. This money is already extending access for children and young people to vital services, and will reach an extra 70,000 children a year by 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to publish a Green Paper on children and young people’s mental health by the end of the year to outline next steps.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-10-10T15:48:02.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767779/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767779/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-14","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve mental health services for children and young people.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","901024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767780","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>Community pharmacies provide vital front line health services. We want them to be even more integrated with the wider health system and used more often by the public for their health needs. We are taking action to make that happen; for example, we have re-commissioned the delivery of flu vaccinations and will be re-running the ‘stay well this winter campaign’ this year.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-10T15:51:02.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767780/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767780/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-14","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to expand the role of pharmacies.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","901028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767781","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>As he knows, NHS England is consulting on draft guidance for commissioners on low value prescription items which includes homeopathic services and medicines. The Government will always support the provision of safe, clinically-effective services for patients, in accordance with NICE recommendations.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-10T15:49:53.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767781/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767781/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-14","NHS: Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the cost implications to the NHS of any withdrawal of NHS homeopathic services and medicines.","false","Biography information for David Tredinnick","Bosworth","David Tredinnick","901025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768273","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>The National Cyber Security Strategy, supported by £1.9 billion of transformational investment, sets out measures to defend our people, businesses, and assets; deter our adversaries; and develop necessary skills and capabilities.</p><p>The National Cyber Security Centre provides advice that helps public and private sector organisations to be more resilient to cyber attacks.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-11T14:48:18.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768273/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768273/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the cyber security of both public and private sector organisations.","false","Biography information for Vicky Ford","Chelmsford","Vicky Ford","900880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768274","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Government takes the threat of cyber attacks against public services very seriously. We support Health and Local Government sectors in improving their cyber resilience and encourage all organisations to implement the NCSC’s advice: to keep software patches up to date, to run antivirus and to back up their data.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-11T14:26:08.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768274/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768274/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Public Sector: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to protect public services against cyber attacks.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","900885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768275","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-11","<p><strong>Voting more than once in a national election is illegal and the Government takes all reports of electoral fraud very seriously. The National Police Chief Council have reported that a number of incidents are being investigated. However, it would be inappropriate to go into more detail whilst investigations are underway. </strong></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-11T14:45:30.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768275/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768275/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","General Election 2017: Election Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many incidents of electoral fraud committed by students double voting were recorded during the 2017 General Election.","false","Biography information for Gareth Snell","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Gareth Snell","900881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760013","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-27","<p>The UK Government remains firmly committed to the promotion and protection of Freedom of Religion or Belief. We regularly raise concerns about the protection and persecution of minority communities, including Ahmadiyya Muslims, the blasphemy laws and the protection of freedom of religion or belief to the Government of Pakistan at a senior level. The Foreign Secretary raised the importance we attach to religious tolerance and safeguarding the rights of all Pakistan's citizens during his visit to Pakistan in November 2016. The former Minister for Asia and the Pacific, my hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Mr Sharma), discussed the protection of religious minorities with Kamran Michael, former Minister for Human Rights, and Barrister Zafarullah Khan, Prime Minister's Special Assistant for Human Rights, during a visit to Pakistan in January 2017.</p><p>We continue to urge Pakistan to take the steps necessary to comply in full with its human rights obligations, including engaging with the UN and other international bodies, and to ensure that the rights of minorities are respected.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-27T16:08:39.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760013/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760013/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Pakistan: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they last raised with the government of Pakistan (1) the anti-Ahmadiyya laws set out in Penal Code Article 298, and (2) that government's obligations to protect freedom of religion or belief; and whether they intend to encourage the government of Pakistan to invite the United Nations Special Rapporteur on Freedom of Religion or Belief to make a country visit to Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760014","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-25","<p>We are aware of the case of Taimoor Raza, a Pakistani national who was sentenced to death on 10 June 2017 after allegedly making blasphemous remarks on social media. We understand Mr Raza has submitted an appeal to the High Court.</p><p>The UK remains firmly opposed to the death penalty in all circumstances. While we have not raised Mr Raza's case directly with the Pakistan authorities, we have repeatedly called upon the Government of Pakistan to end capital punishment and, at a minimum, commit to publicly renewing the previously imposed moratorium on the death penalty. We regularly raise our concerns about freedom of expression and the misuse of the blasphemy laws with the Pakistani Government at a senior level.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary raised misuse of the blasphemy laws during his visit to Pakistan in November 2016. The former Minister for Asia and the Pacific, my hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Mr Sharma), discussed the death penalty and the importance we attach to freedom of expression with Kamran Michael, former Minister for Human Rights, and Barrister Zafarullah Khan, Prime Minister's Special Assistant for Human Rights, during a visit to Pakistan in January 2017. The Government will continue to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to the death penalty and freedom of expression and religion.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-25T14:38:37.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760014/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760014/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Taimoor Raza","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what information they have about the case of Taimoor Raza who has been sentenced to death in Pakistan for allegedly breaking the blasphemy laws on social media; and what representations, if any, they have made on his behalf.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760015","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-21","<p>DFID’s education programmes in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and Punjab provinces continue to support provincial governments in the ongoing process to update and revise textbooks. In Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and Punjab lower secondary textbooks are now the focus. Through the Ilm Two programme DFID is directly supporting the production of additional reading materials that specifically focus on religious tolerance and inclusion. DFID is also engaged with Federal Government consultations on a new draft National Curriculum which is in its early stages. The Federal Government has also agreed minimum standards for educational quality which were adopted by provinces this year. These standards set the quality criteria for learners, curriculum, textbooks<strong>,</strong> teachers and assessment and form the basis for the current textbook reform.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-09-21T12:01:46.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760015/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760015/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-13","Pakistan: Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the meeting of Lord Alton of Liverpool and Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne with the Minister of State at the Department for International Development, Rory Stewart MP, about the role of school textbooks and the school curriculum in Pakistan in describing non-Muslims, what progress has been made in promoting inclusive educational approaches in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760016","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-21","<p>The Action Plan for Human Rights, published by the Pakistan Ministry of Human Rights in 2016, contains proposals for a range of measures to improve human rights in Pakistan, including a National Commission for Minorities and security arrangements for protection of places of worship of minorities. We have encouraged implementation of the Action Plan.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-21T15:02:27.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760016/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760016/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Pakistan: Minority Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what information they have about proposals in Pakistan to establish (1) a National Council for Minorities’ Rights, and (2) a dedicated police unit to protect religious minorities; and whether they have encouraged such developments.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760017","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-21","<p>The Ministry of Human Rights in Pakistan is currently reviewing the Christian Marriage Act 1872 and Christian Divorce Act 1862. We have discussed the review with the then Minister for Human Rights, Kamran Michael, and regularly raise minority and women's rights with the Government of Pakistan.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-21T14:57:31.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760017/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760017/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Pakistan: Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have encouraged the government of Pakistan to enact laws recognising the legality of Christian marriages.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760018","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-21","<p>The DFID Annual Report includes the following figures for aid spend in Pakistan for the last five years;</p><p> </p><p>2012-13 £203.1 Million</p><p>2013-14 £253 M</p><p>2014-15 £249 M</p><p>2015-16 £336.2 M</p><p>2016-17 £422.1M</p><p> </p><p>£39.5 million has been committed to the Voice and Accountability programme (AAWAZ) which aims to ensure that democratic processes are more open, inclusive and accountable to citizens in Pakistan. It focuses on three areas:</p><p> </p><p>1- Women’s and minority rights, their political participation and decision making;</p><p>2- Tolerance and prevention of violence (inter-faith, sectarian and gender-based)</p><p>3- Increasing the accountability and responsiveness of the state to citizens’ demands for improved service delivery (particularly on health and education).</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-09-21T12:02:54.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760018/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760018/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-13","Pakistan: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much overseas aid they have given to Pakistan in each of the past five years; and of that, how much has specifically been committed to the promotion of (1) the protection of minorities, and (2) freedom of religion or belief.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760019","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>Not all community transport operators are required to hold a PSV operator’s licence. This only applies to operators who do not fit into one of the relevant exemptions to EU Regulation 1071/2009, which has applied in the UK since 2011.</p><p> </p><p>We will consult on the issue and use of section 19 and section 22 permits later this year. The consultation will be accompanied by an Impact Assessment focussing on the potential effects for operators who use permits.</p><p>We are working with community transport and local authority organisations to understand better the potential impacts.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-09-20T13:03:13.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760019/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760019/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Community Transport: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have undertaken an impact assessment of the effect on individuals and communities unable to access conventional bus services of their proposals to require community transport operators to hold a conventional PCV operator's licence.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL1575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760020","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-25","<p>The UK levies corporation tax on companies based on the profits generated by their economic activity undertaken in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has announced a number of recent changes to reinforce that principle, including a restriction to the deductibility of corporate interest expense, which is due to increase receipts by around £1bn per annum.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also continues to consider, at both a domestic and international level, whether the existing tax rules deliver that principle for new digital business models. For instance, the UK actively supports the OECD’s Task Force on the Digital Economy, which has been mandated to explore these issues.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-09-25T09:59:44.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760020/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760020/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Amazon: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the conclusions of the report by the Centre for Economics and Business Research Bookselling Britain that bookshops pay 11 times more tax than Amazon, and whether they have plans to address this.","false","Biography information for Lord Hain",,"Lord Hain","HL1576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760021","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-04","<p>In 2016, there were 2,005 retail units specialised in selling books in the UK, compared to 2,055 in 2010 (ONS business counts).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-10-04T11:40:02.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760021/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760021/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Shops: Closures","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many bookshops have closed in the UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Hain",,"Lord Hain","HL1577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760022","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-20","<p>As the Chief Secretary to the Treasury set out in the Written Ministerial Statement laid on 12<sup>th</sup> September, pay awards for 2017/18 for police and prison officers will be funded within existing budgets.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-09-20T10:38:25.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760022/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760022/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Police and Prison Officers: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether pay increases during this financial year for police and prison officers will be paid for from existing budgets.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL1578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760023","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-19","<p>We engage with continental media daily to set out our plans for a deep and special future partnership with the EU27. Engagement is conducted directly through briefings with EU correspondents in the UK, via our team in UKRep in Brussels and through our network of Embassies in Member States.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-09-19T12:46:37.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760023/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760023/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have used the continental media as a way of presenting to the public in the EU–27 their case for a constructive future relationship with the EU; and what plans they have to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760024","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-21","<p>Support for international criminal justice and accountability is a fundamental element of UK foreign policy. International courts and tribunals, including the International Criminal Court, have an important role to play in global efforts to end impunity for the most serious crimes of international concern by holding perpetrators to account and achieving justice for victims. The institutions report regularly on their activities and publish up-to-date details of convictions and sentences on their publicly accessible websites. The Government does not intend to publish a summary of such information at this time.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-21T15:04:00.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760024/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760024/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","International Courts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to publish a summary of the verdicts and punishments imposed by all international courts and tribunals associated with the United Nations relating to breaches by individuals of international law in the last 20 years, including those imposed by the International Criminal Court.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760025","Department of Health","false","2017-09-21","<p>Clinical peer reviews are a simple way for general practitioners (GPs) to support each other and help patients get the best care, from the right person at the right time, without having to make unnecessary trips to hospital. More than half of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have already implemented some form of clinical peer review system and the NHS England guidance will help ensure best practice is shared to the remaining local commissioners.</p><p> </p><p>There is flexibility in how local CCGs and their GPs implement prospective internal clinical peer review, but it should see GPs reviewing each other’s new referrals to provide constructive feedback in a safe learning environment. Delivering prospective internal peer review will help ensure that all patients get access to the optimum care pathway. It should not be established as an approval process and the referring GP retains responsibility for the patient and makes the final decision.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-09-21T12:09:27.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760025/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760025/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","General Practitioners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the guidance issued by NHS England to clinical commissioning groups in May stating that all areas of the country should have a system in place from September to ensure that all new GP referrals are subject to clinical peer review, how they define such reviews.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760026","Department of Health","false","2017-09-21","<p>The Department and the Government Legal Department do not categorise cases as specifically relating to ‘public health’. According to Government Legal Department records, the approximate total number of judicial review cases brought against the Department in each of the last five years is shown in the following table. 42 cases are recorded as active as of 15 September 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of cases brought</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>117</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source: </em>Data from the Government Legal Department.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-09-21T12:10:21.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760026/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760026/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Department of Health: Judicial Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many legal cases have been filed against the Department of Health about public health matters in each of the last five years; and how many are currently in progress.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760027","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>My Hon Friend, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Transport, the Hon Member for Blackpool North and Cleveleys (Paul Maynard MP) as Rail Minister met with GTR in June and the Secretary of State met with GTR in July.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-09-20T13:04:07.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760027/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760027/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Southern","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when ministers last (1) met, and (2) had discussions with, representatives of Southern Rail.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760028","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>Ministers receive numerous representations about Southern Rail from individuals and organisations – through both formal and informal channels. The government is committed to making sure passengers receive the reliable, high quality services on Southern they deserve, and I am encouraged that the Public Performance Measure of punctuality is currently at 82% compared to 62% in early December 2016.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-09-20T13:04:40.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760028/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760028/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Southern: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations ministers have received regarding passenger services on Southern Rail.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760029","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>The quality of passenger services on Southern Rail has been significantly better since the New Year with the Public Performance Measure of punctuality currently at 82%, compared to 62% in early December 2016. The latest National Rail Passenger Survey showed a 7% increase in overall journey satisfaction on Southern Rail compared with the previous survey.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-09-20T13:06:03.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760029/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760029/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Southern: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the quality of passenger services on Southern Rail.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760030","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-19","<p>A future partnership between the UK and EU is in the interests of both sides, and we have entered into the negotiations anticipating success. However, since the result of the referendum, we have taken the responsible approach to work at pace to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will affect policies and services for a range of outcomes, including the unlikely scenario in which no mutually satisfactory agreement can be reached.</p><p>Given the long lead-in times to implement some of our contingency measures, we need to begin now for them to remain viable. But implementing the first stages of contingency plans now should not be interpreted as an expectation that talks with the EU will not be successful, and we are clear that securing a good deal for both sides is by far and away the highest probability, but we have a duty to plan for the alternative. These are the actions of a responsible government determined to ensure a smooth exit under any eventuality.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-09-19T14:17:20.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760030/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760030/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have made for the UK to leave the EU in March 2019 in the event that the European Council or the European Parliament does not ratify any agreement reached between the UK and the European Commission concerning the UK’s departure from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760032","Attorney General","false","2017-10-09","<p>The information requested is containing in the following tables, broken down into the different Law Officers' Departments.</p><p><strong>SFO</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Individuals leaving the SFO under exit schemes since 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total payment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>£281k</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>£324k</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Attorney General’s Office (AGO), the Government Legal Department (GLD) and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Individuals leaving the AGO, GLD and HMCPSI under exit schemes since 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total payment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>Fewer than 5</p></td><td><p>£172,148</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>Fewer than 5</p></td><td><p>£317,933</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Since 31 March 2016, there have been 5 or fewer men and 5 or fewer women who have left the Attorney General’s Office (AGO), the Government Legal Department (GLD) and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI) under an early exit scheme.</p><p><strong>CPS</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Individuals leaving the CPS under exit schemes since 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total payment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>£1,024,651</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>£500,040</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-10-09T09:36:29.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760032/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760032/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-13","Attorney General: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many (a) men and (b) women have left the Law Officers' Departments under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760033","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-13","<p>The Government is determined to protect the Armed Forces against improper legal claims. That is why we asked the Solicitors Regulation Authority to investigate solicitor Phil Shiner, who was struck off earlier this year for dishonesty. In respect of Northern Ireland, the Defence Secretary is working closely with the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland to ensure that the approach taken to address Northern Ireland's past is fair, balanced, and proportionate and that veterans are fully supported throughout.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-13T13:06:47.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760033/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760033/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Armed Forces: Administration of Justice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that reprisals against former or current members of the armed forces through the legal system for political reasons are not allowed.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","10314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760034","Attorney General","false","2017-10-09","<p>The information requested is detailed in the following tables.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Serious Fraud Office: Pay increase</strong><sup>1</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Above 1%</p></td><td><p>At 1%</p></td><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>141</p></td><td><p>146</p></td><td><p>48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>291</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>96</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>36</p></td><td><p>59</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em><sup>1</sup></em><em> Based on staff in post as at 31 August in each of the past three years.</em></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Attorney General’s Office (AGO)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Above 1%</p></td><td><p>At 1%</p></td><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Government Legal Department (GLD)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Above 1%</p></td><td><p>At 1%</p></td><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>65</p></td><td><p>973</p></td><td><p>96</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>848</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>578</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>834</p></td><td><p>105</p></td><td><p>1006</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Above 1%</p></td><td><p>At 1%</p></td><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>More than 1%</p></td><td><p>At 1%</p></td><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1,038</p></td><td><p>3,743</p></td><td><p>1,881</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>1,075</p></td><td><p>3,445</p></td><td><p>1,760</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>675</p></td><td><p>3,058</p></td><td><p>2,182</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In relation to the CPS:</p><ul><li><p>In each of the three years the average pay awards were limited to up to 1% in line with the government’s framework from which all departments have set their pay arrangements.</p></li></ul><p>In relation to the GLD, AGO and HMCPSI:</p><ul><li><p>The pay award in 2014 provided all staff with a 1% pay award although a number received part of this as a non-consolidated sum because they were on or near their grade maximum and a small number had a retained contractual entitlement to a specific pay award of more than 1% from a previous department.</p></li><li><p>The 2015 and 2016 pay awards provided staff with a cash sum based on 1% of the average salary for their grade. The outcome provided an award of greater than 1% for those who were at the lower end of their pay range and less than 1% for those at the upper end.</p></li><li><p>GLD also took the opportunity in 2016 to review and update the pay structure for Legal Trainees and Legal Officers, resulting in a higher than 1% award in that year as individual’s moved to the new structure (30 people benefitted in this way).</p></li></ul><p>In relation to the SFO:</p><ul><li><p>For the 2014 pay award the SFO paid all eligible staff an award of either £350 or 1%. Ineligible staff were those already earning in excess of their pay-band maximum, those staff who were deemed as not effective and those staff who had joined the SFO after 31 January 2014.</p></li><li><p>In 2015, the SFO sought and obtained Treasury and AGO approval to convert 0.5% of the accrued bonus pot to fund increases to base pay for the more junior digital forensic and investigator roles. This was to help with retention and recruitment of staff in those roles which had been identified as a business need. At the same time the SFO introduced a performance pay matrix which allowed for strong performers near to the bottom of their pay-band to receive a larger increase than those in the middle and top of the band. Eligibility criteria were the same as for 2014 – with the cut-off date for new staff being 31 January 2015.</p></li><li><p>In April 2016 the SFO introduced a new pay model, also approved by Treasury and the Attorney General, which created separate specialist pay-bands for corporate, operational and digital staff to again further improve the recruitment/retention position with key operational roles. This allowed for a further significant base pay increases for staff in digital and investigative roles at all grades. The annual pay award in August 2016 followed the same approach as for 2015.</p></li></ul>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-10-09T09:36:52.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760034/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760034/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-13","Attorney General: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many of the Law Officers Departments' staff had a pay increase (a) above one per cent, (b) at one per cent and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760035","Attorney General","false","2017-10-09","<p>Since 2012 there have been no civil servants in the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) who are employed by the Government Commercial Function.</p><p>The Attorney General’s Office (AGO), the Government Legal Department (GLD), Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI) and the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) do not have any staff who are part of the Government Commercial Function.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-10-09T09:37:09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760035/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760035/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-13","Attorney General: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many civil servants in the Law Officers' Departments are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside Government and (b) in from outside the government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760036","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government Commercial Function is staffed by employees working across many Civil<br>Service Departments. Within the Cabinet Office as at 30 th September 2017, there are 27.5<br>FTE in the Government Commercial Function who set the vision and direction of the<br>Government Commercial Function and support the running of the Government<br>Commercial Organisation.</p><p>The Government Commercial Organisation (GCO), founded in 2016, is the Central<br>employer of senior Commercial staff across the Civil Service. As at 30 th September 2017 it<br>employs 220 people as part of the Cabinet Office. Members of the GCO all sit within<br>government departments, working on commercial contracts within those departments. Two<br>members of the GCO are out on secondment, to MHRA and NEST. No members of the<br>GCO have been seconded in to the Civil Service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-19T12:04:35.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760036/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760036/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-13","Cabinet Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside of government and (b) in from outside of the government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760037","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The process for reimbursing properly incurred costs for electoral events is overseen by the<br>Election Claims Unit. Once claims have been received and properly scrutinised, expenses<br>necessarily incurred for the effective and efficient delivery of the poll will be reimbursed</p><p>The Election Claims Unit aims to settle claims within 12 months of them being received.</p><p>The majority of electoral registration activity is funded by local authorities across England,<br>Scotland and Wales. The law does not allow for claims for electoral events to include costs<br>of electoral registration.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-20T14:54:00.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760037/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760037/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-13","Elections: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will take steps to ensure that all costs properly incurred in (a) the administration of elections, including electoral registration costs directly attributable to the election, are reimbursed to returning officers and their employing local authorities and (b) delivering electoral registration are automatically provided to local authorities without the need to revert to the justification-led bidding process.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760038","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>Details of exits from my Department are routinely published in the Department’s Annual<br>Report and Accounts. These are available on the Cabinet Office website at<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office- annual-reports- and-accounts</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T15:05:04.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760038/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760038/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-13","Cabinet Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760039","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-11","<p>When numbers are so small that individuals could be identified, identifying details are masked to protect their privacy. Starting on and including the 1 April 2016 the Department has had 5 or fewer men and 5 or fewer women leave under exit schemes.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-11T11:24:54.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760039/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760039/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Treasury: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760040","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Mineworkers’ Pension Scheme is administered by the Scheme’s Trustees. Therefore, the Department does not hold this information. Requests such as this should be directed to the Scheme’s Trustees.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-09T15:46:49.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760040/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760040/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much the average pension payment from the Mineworkers Pension Scheme has been in the last 12 months; and how many such payments amount to less than (a) £10, (b) £20 and (c) £50 per week.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","10332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760041","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>No estimate has been carried out on the cost of providing tax relief for non-taxpayers enrolled in net-pay schemes. Legislation determines the difference between net-pay and relief-at-source systems, and ultimately, it is for pension schemes to choose which to apply. To help employers choose an appropriate pension scheme, The Pensions Regulator offers guidance, including information on the different methods by which tax incentives are obtained.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-09T12:53:27.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760041/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760041/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of providing the 20 per cent tax relief to non-taxpayers enrolled in net-pay-arrangement defined contribution pension schemes on the same basis as is provided in relief-at-source schemes; and how many people are not benefiting from that relief.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","10359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760042","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>HMT conducts an annual business planning round and the Executive Management Board delegates budgets and headcount targets to Directors. Within these constraints, Directors are free to make their own resourcing decisions, including whether to make use of temporary staff. Historically, the use of temporary staff has been very low in HMT.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-09T15:56:05.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760042/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760042/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Treasury: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7983, on Treasury: temporary employment, for what reasons his Department does not have a resource board.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760043","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government continues to work with the Bank of England and Financial Conduct Authority to assess how the UK’s exit from the EU could impact financial services firms, and is alive to the risk that the UK’s withdrawal could in some cases create legal uncertainties regarding the status of existing cross-border financial services contracts.</p><p> </p><p>As noted in the record of its meeting on 20 September 2017, these and other issues that the Financial Policy Committee (FPC) have identified pose risks to the provision of financial services in both the European Union and the United Kingdom. The FPC also highlighted in its June Financial Stability Report the risk of market fragmentation as the UK leaves the EU, which could result in higher costs and greater risks for both EU and UK companies and households.</p><p> </p><p>There is a shared interest for both the UK and the EU in ensuring that we avoid outcomes that impose unnecessary costs and disruption to UK and EU individuals and businesses as the UK leaves the EU.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-09T15:53:10.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760043/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760043/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Financial Services: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether existing contracts that underpin cross-border financial transactions within the EU of financial institutions based in the UK will continue to be valid when the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","10390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760044","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Barnett consequentials for the years covered by the 2015 Spending Review arising from the Telecommunications Infrastructure (Relief from Non-domestic Rates) Bill are set out below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>£ million</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scottish Government</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Welsh Government</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland Executive</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-09T13:13:44.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760044/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760044/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Telecommunications: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what Barnet consequentials arise from the Telecommunications Infrastructure (Relief from Non-domestic Rates) Bill for (a) Scotland, (b) Wales and (c) Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760045","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>This PQ can only be responded to fully at a disproportionate cost as data held includes other salary increases (e.g. promotion increases) besides the annual pay award increases.</p><p> </p><p>The annual pay awards for the delegated grades (i.e. below Senior Civil Service) have been applied in accordance with HM Treasury pay guidance that restricts increases in paybill to an average of one per cent across all staff. Over the last few years, the department has targeted pay awards so that lower paid staff receive higher awards than those at the top of pay ranges.</p><p> </p><p>The annual pay arrangements for the Senior Civil Service are based on the outcomes of the Senior Salaries Review Body Report and the Government’s response to its recommendations. The arrangements are applied centrally by Cabinet Office. Over the last three years, pay awards for HM Treasury senior civil servants have based on their performance and their position in the pay range. Overall, an average award of 1% has applied to this group of staff, in each year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-09T15:57:14.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760045/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760045/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above one per cent, (b) at one per cent and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760046","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-11","<p>HM Treasury has no record of any employee being part of the Government Commercial Function.</p><p>HM Treasury has no record of any staff being seconded in or out of the department to the Government Commercial Function from 2012.</p><p>HMT outsourced its procurement function to Crown Commercial Service in 2013</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-11T11:27:22.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760046/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760046/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Treasury: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside of government and (b) in from outside of the government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760047","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-10","<p>This information is all publicly available.</p><p> </p><p>The European Investment Bank (EIB) publishes details of all projects including dates of approval and signature and total signed amounts. Information on UK EIB projects can be found in the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.eib.org/projects/loan/list/?region=1&amp;country=GB" target="_blank">http://www.eib.org/projects/loan/list/?region=1&amp;country=GB</a></p><p> </p><p>The European Investment Fund also publish information on all newly signed operations on their website including signature dates and amounts invested. This can be found in the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.eif.org/news_centre/press_releases/all/index.htm" target="_blank">http://www.eif.org/news_centre/press_releases/all/index.htm</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-10T12:54:57.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760047/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760047/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","New Businesses: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7295, how much funding UK companies have received from the (a) European Investment Bank and the (b) European Investment Fund in (i) each of the last three years and (ii) each month of the 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","10429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760048","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Analysis conducted by HM Treasury shows that on average, when including employer pension contributions, there is a public sector pay premium of about 10%, and excluding employer pension contributions, public and private sector pay is, on average, now around the same level.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-09T15:33:15.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760048/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760048/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 24 July 2017 to Question HL1074, if he will publish figures for the estimated differential between public and private sector pay when employer pension contributions are excluded.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","10430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760049","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>HM Treasury ministers have discussions with representatives from the devolved administrations on a regular basis on matters of importance to the economies of Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and the UK.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-09T15:35:30.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760049/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760049/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Treasury: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers from his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760050","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Since the last update to Parliament in November 2016, HMRC has tripled the number of criminal and civil investigations linked to the Panama papers.</p><p>To date, the work of the Panama Papers Taskforce has led to civil and criminal investigations into 66 individuals for suspected tax evasion, including high net worth individuals. As part of this HMRC has made four arrests; and carried out six interviews under caution.</p><p>Taskforce partners have made three arrests in relation to an organised crime group suspected of a £125m conspiracy to defraud pension investors, tax evasion and associated money laundering. They have also identified leads relevant to a major insider trading operation, in relation to which a number of individuals have been arrested and are on bail pending further activity.</p><p>UK law enforcement continues to interrogate and exploit Panama Papers related data, identifying previously unknown individuals, companies and properties, making links between them and providing intelligence and investigative opportunities.</p><p>The systems used to launder money and evade tax through offshore structures are complex and highly sophisticated. The Joint Financial Analysis Centre and HMRC’s expert analysts are using leading-edge technology to unpick these structures and trace them back to individuals. This work is painstaking and forensic and there are no easy shortcuts.</p><p>HMRC is not a prosecuting authority. Its focus is on building the strongest possible cases in order to secure convictions, and it expects to refer cases to the prosecuting authorities from autumn 2017 onwards.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T15:05:18.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760050/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760050/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many UK nationals have (a) been prosecuted and (b) received a prison sentence for offences related to the Panama Papers data leak.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","10475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760051","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government supports the recommendation in the recent Financial Advice Market Review (FAMR) against the introduction of a fixed 15-year long-stop. A fixed 15-year long-stop is not in the interests of consumers as it could limit the protection available on long-term investment products, where consumers may not realise they have a cause for complaint for more than 15 years. It is important that consumers can seek redress where it is due, so that they have the confidence to engage with financial services firms.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-09T15:49:13.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760051/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760051/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Financial Services: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to establish limited liability for independent financial advisors with the introduction of a fixed 15-year long-stop.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","10466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760052","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State and other Ministers of the Department for Communities and Local Government have regular meetings with the devolved administrations to discuss a range of issues.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-12T16:17:50.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760052/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760052/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers from his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760053","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government has not transferred any civil servants to the Government Commercial Function to date.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-09T10:10:47.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760053/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760053/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside of government and (b) in from outside of the government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760054","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on our plans, including the role of local authorities, later in the Autumn.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","10408","2017-10-09T10:08:31.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760054/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760054/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish documents relating to the next round of consultation on proposals to reform the funding arrangements for supported housing.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760055","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans later in the autumn.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T11:59:49.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760055/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760055/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of linking funding for supported housing to local housing allowance rates.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760056","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-13","<p>Decisions of this nature are properly the responsibility of the local authority. Ministers have no remit to intervene in the day to day affairs of local authorities, except where specific provision has been made in an Act of Parliament.</p><p>Complaints about how any such decision has been reached should be considered against the Council’s code of conduct, and directed in the first instance towards the Council’s statutory monitoring officer, who has a duty to investigate.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-13T12:49:22.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760056/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760056/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Electric Cables: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to investigate the leader of Gloucestershire County Council on whether he acted ultra vires by agreeing to the cabling from the energy firm waste plant at Javelin Park at Junction 13 on the M5 through to the Ryeford Substation via Stonehouse High Street.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","10388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760057","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-13","<p>The decision on whether an environmental impact assessment is required is a matter for the local planning authority.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-13T16:25:16.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760057/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760057/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Electric Cables: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to ensure that Gloucestershire County Council undertakes environmental impact assessment on the impact of installing a cable from Javelin Park to the Ryeford Substation via Stonehouse High Street","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","10389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760058","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on our plans, including the role of local authorities, later in the Autumn.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","10410","2017-10-09T10:08:31.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760058/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760058/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect on local authorities of the proposed reform of funding for supported housing.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760059","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-03","<p>Nationals of the European Economic Area are eligible for an allocation of social housing if they have a relevant right to reside in the UK under EU law, for example, if they are working, are self-employed, or have a permanent right of residence (after 5 years lawful residence in the UK).</p><p>We do not collect information on the levels of discrimination against EU nationals in relation to housing in the private or social rented sector.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-03T17:17:05.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760059/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760059/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-13","Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what monitoring of levels of discrimination against EU citizens in the UK in the fields of securing housing in the (a) private and (b) social sectors his Department has conducted since June 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760060","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Since 31 March 2016, the number of men and women who have left the Department under exit schemes is:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><ol><li><p>Men: 2</p></li><li><p>Women: 4</p></li></ol><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-09T12:15:22.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760060/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760060/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) men and (b) women have left her Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760061","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government does not hold this information. The BBC, under its trademark 'TV Licensing', carries out the administration and enforcement of the television licence system.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-09T10:00:58.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760061/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760061/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many households were demonstrated to own a television set but did not have a television license in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","10354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760062","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-13","<p>DCMS participates in the Government Commercial Organisation (GCO) scheme, which is part of Cabinet Office.</p><p> </p><p>In the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS), one civil servant is currently part of the Government Commercial Organisation. The individual has not been seconded outside Government, as part of GCO, in any year since 2012 and was not seconded in.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-13T12:16:10.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760062/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760062/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many civil servants in her Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded(a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760063","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>DCMS participates in the Government Commercial Organisation (GCO) scheme, which is part of Cabinet Office.</p><p> </p><p>In the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS), one civil servant is part of the Government Commercial Organisation. The individual has not been seconded outside Government, as part of GCO, and was not seconded in.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T08:46:52.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760063/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760063/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many civil servants of her Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been (a) seconded outside of government and (b) seconded in from outside of government since her Department was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760064","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Department does not have data on premises that receive speeds of less than 5Mbps. The Department has deposited in the House of Commons Library results of its modelling and analysis of broadband coverage by constituency, including figures for sub 2 and sub 10 Mbps premises. Similar information, by constituency, is also available from Think Broadband (http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/).</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-09T12:19:23.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760064/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760064/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many households received broadband speeds of less than 5mb in each constituency in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","10423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760065","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-22","<p>The table below lists the most recent meetings between Ministers from DCMS and their counterparts in the devolved administrations and the next planned meetings:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Minister</p></td><td><p>Devolved Administration</p></td><td><p>Date of most recent meeting</p></td><td><p>Next planned meeting</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media &amp; Sport</p></td><td><p>Welsh Government</p></td><td><p>26 September 2016</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minister for Digital</p></td><td><p>Scottish Government</p></td><td><p>6<sup>th</sup> November</p></td><td><p>28<sup>th</sup> November 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minister for Sport &amp; Civil Society</p></td><td><p>Welsh Government</p></td><td><p>20<sup>th</sup> November 2016</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minister for Arts, Heritage and Tourism</p></td><td><p>Welsh, Scottish and Northern Ireland Governments</p></td><td><p>26<sup>th</sup> October</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-22T15:17:24.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760065/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760065/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers from her Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760066","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>As I made clear at Departmental Oral Questions on 18 September, I am determined that the gambling industry acknowledges its social responsibilities, including properly funding the work undertaken by GambleAware, and other organisations, on research, education and treatment for gambling-related harm.</p><p> </p><p>The industry currently contributes over £8 million per year to GambleAware. GambleAware is seeking to increase this to £10 million per year in line with work that has been done by the Responsible Gambling Strategy Board (RGSB) to cost the short term work of delivering the National Responsible Gambling Strategy.</p><p>The industry must step up and fulfill their obligations under these new targets.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-09T11:14:30.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760066/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760066/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-13","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing a statutory levy on bookmakers to fund the work of GambleAware.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","10477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760067","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-10","<p>The plan is for the UK/Poland Bilateral Defence Cooperation Treaty to be signed by the end of this calendar year, at the next PM-led Inter-Governmental Consultations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-10T14:32:45.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760067/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760067/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Poland: Military Alliances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the Government plans to sign the defence co-operation treaty with Poland announced in the joint communiqué issued in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","10468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760068","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-10","<p>As at 15 September 2017, 1,940 Ministry of Defence (MOD) civil servants were part of the Government Commercial Function.</p><p>Since 2012, 20 MOD civil servants within the Commercial Function have been seconded to non- Governmental organisations.</p><p>Individuals seconded into the MOD from non-Governmental organisations would not be classed as civil servants if they remained on their former company's payroll. Those who do transfer onto the MOD payroll would no longer be classed as secondees.</p><p>Note: Numbers provided have been rounded to the nearest five.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-10T14:29:28.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760068/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760068/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside of government and (b) in from outside of government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760069","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) regularly reviews its requirements for linguists and trains its personnel accordingly. The level of Arabic language proficiency in the MOD is sufficient to meet current Defence needs.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-10T14:53:17.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760069/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760069/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Ministry of Defence: Arabic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his most recent assessment is of the level of Arabic-language proficiency in his Department.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760070","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-11","<p>Officials in the Ministry of Defence's Operations Directorate work with a network of staff in wider Defence teams, other government departments, and staff in our Embassies to identify reports of potential international humanitarian law violations from a broad range of English and Arabic language press and social media sources. This network includes staff with Arabic language skills.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","10374","2017-10-11T15:41:17.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760070/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760070/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many officials in the operations directorate conduct searches for media reporting of violations of international humanitarian law by the Saudi-led coalition in Yemen; and how many of those staff have a working knowledge of Arabic.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760071","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-11","<p>Officials in the Ministry of Defence's Operations Directorate work with a network of staff in wider Defence teams, other government departments, and staff in our Embassies to identify reports of potential international humanitarian law violations from a broad range of English and Arabic language press and social media sources. This network includes staff with Arabic language skills.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","10373","2017-10-11T15:41:17.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760071/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760071/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether officials in the operations directorate responsible for conducting searches for media reporting of violations of international humanitarian law by the Saudi-led coalition in Yemen search Arabic-language press and social media; and whether those reports are included in the Ministry of Defence Database.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760073","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-09","<p>The value of current contracts between the Ministry of Defence and Boeing is around £4.5 billion.</p><p>The largest contract held is the Chinook through life customer support contract which is valued at over £2 billion and runs until 2040.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-09T15:17:30.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760073/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760073/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-13","Boeing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the value is of current Government procurement contracts with the Boeing Company.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","10361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760074","Department for Education","false","2017-10-09","<p>When numbers are so small that individuals could be identified, identifying details are masked to protect their privacy. Since 31 March 2016, fewer than five individuals have left the Department for Education under an exit scheme and a total of £95,000 has been paid.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-09T17:48:39.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760074/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760074/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-13","Department for Education: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) men and (b) women have left her Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760075","Department for Education","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department completed a range of background checks on Johnson Kane and gained assurance that The Education Followship Trust had conducted their own due diligence.</p><p> </p><p>Personal information held by the Department is regarded as confidential and is not normally disclosed publicly or to third parties without the consent of the person concerned.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-12T16:19:18.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760075/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760075/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-13","Johnson Kane","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will set out the information obtained by background checks carried out by her Department on Johnson Kane, the co-founder and Chief Executive Officer of the Education Fellowship Trust.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","10367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760076","Department for Education","false","2017-10-09","<p>The additional £1.3 billion we are investing in schools will ensure the new national funding formula provides a cash increase of at least 1% per pupil by 2019-20 for every school, with up to 3% gains per pupil, per year, for underfunded schools, to enable all schools to provide the right support to their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>Funding is not allocated directly by reference to when in the year children are born. Within the national funding formula, additional funding is directed by reference to the number of children who have low prior attainment, and have fallen behind their peers.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-09T11:24:21.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760076/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760076/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-13","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that schools have additional financial resources to aid them in better supporting summer born children.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","10391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760077","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-10","<p>The independent Low Pay Commission (LPC) review and recommend the National Minimum Wage rates each year, following extensive consultation and analysis. Their recommendations for 2018 will be provided to the Government in autumn, and Ministers will announce the rates, including the apprentice rate, to apply from April 2018 following that.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-10T14:40:18.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760077/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760077/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Apprentices: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government has plans to increase the national living wage for apprentices above £3.50 per hour.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","10385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760078","Department for Education","false","2017-10-09","<p>As at 31 July 2017, there were 64 civil servants working within the commercial function at the Department for Education. All departmental commercial professionals are members of the Government Commercial Function.</p><p>Our records show that one civil servant employed within the commercial function at Department for Education was seconded outside the Government in 2012. There have been no inward secondees from outside the Government at any time since 2012.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-09T17:53:21.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760078/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760078/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-13","Department for Education: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many civil servants in her Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded(a) outside of government and (b) in from outside of overnment in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760079","Department for Education","false","2017-10-09","<p>My Rt hon. Friend, the Minister of State for School Standards and Minister for Equalities, met John Swinney MSP, Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills, and Kirsty Williams AM, Cabinet Secretary for Education, on 30 March 2017.</p><p>My hon. Friend, the Minister of State for Universities, Science, Research, met Kirsty Williams AM, Cabinet Secretary for Education, on 20 December 2016.</p><p>Education is a power that is devolved to Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. My Ministerial colleagues do not currently have planned meetings with their counterparts in the devolved administrations, however there is ongoing dialogue at official level.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-09T17:50:57.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760079/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760079/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-13","Department for Education: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers from her Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760080","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-09","<p>There has been extensive engagement at ministerial and official level between Defra and the devolved administrations (DAs). The Secretary of State made it a priority to engage with Scottish and Welsh Government counterparts by making phone calls during his first week of office.</p><p> </p><p>This summer, the Secretary of State meet with the Scottish Government Cabinet Secretary, Fergus Ewing, at the Royal Highland Show on 22<sup>nd</sup> June, and the Welsh Government Cabinet Secretary, Lesley Griffiths, at the Royal Welsh Show on 24<sup>th</sup> July. The Secretary of State also met with the Permanent Secretary in Northern Ireland’s Department for Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs (DAERA) at the Antrim Show on 22<sup>nd</sup> July.</p><p> </p><p>Minister Therese Coffey met with Fergus Ewing MSP during a forestry visit to Scotland on 27<sup>th</sup> June.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State met ministerial counterparts in the Welsh and Scottish Governments, along with a senior official from DAERA (NIE), on 25<sup>th</sup> September for on-going discussions on the UK’s withdrawal from the EU. The next meeting is currently being planned for the end of October.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-09T11:48:50.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760080/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760080/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers from his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760081","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-10","<p><br></p><p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs currently has no civil servants that are part of the Government Commercial Function. Defra's Commercial Director was part of the Government Commercial Function but has recently left the department.</p><p><br></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-10T10:24:21.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760081/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760081/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded  (a) outside of government and (b) in from outside of government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760082","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-12","<p>Defra has not conducted any specific surveys of the economic value of the recreational bass fishery over the last ten years. The Defra ‘Sea Angling 2012’ research project found that, in 2012, sea anglers resident in England spent £1.23 billion on the sport. It is not possible robustly to separate out figures specifically for recreational bass fishing.</p><p>Bass conservation measures have been introduced by the EU in response to advice from the International Council for the Exploration of the Sea on the very poor state of the stock. Alongside a significant reduction in commercial landings, these measures are aimed at reducing mortality while the stock recovers, in order to secure the long term future of bass fisheries. The EU measures from 2015 onwards were also applied to the recreational sector as scientific advice in 2014 indicated on the basis of earlier angling surveys that up to 25% of total bass removals were estimated at that time to be accounted for by bass anglers.</p><p>A specific cost estimate of the effects of the EU bass recovery measures on the recreational sector by limiting retention of catch by anglers has not been conducted. Arriving at a reliable assessment, particularly given that catch and release activity has not been restricted, would be challenging. There would need to be a wide range of factors covered in such an evaluation, including the reduced availability of bass while stocks are recovering, and the need to take into account the longer term costs of failing to apply sufficient bass recovery measures across all fishing sectors. This places the emphasis on ensuring recovery measures are in place that will restore the value of bass fisheries across all fishing sectors.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","105168","2017-10-12T16:47:06.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760082/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760082/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-13","Angling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the value of recreational bass fishing in England to the economy in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","10364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760083","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>We are conducting rigorous analysis of various trade scenarios on UK agriculture as part of our planning. This analysis will be ongoing, helping to develop a detailed understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will impact on the UK to best inform government policy going forward.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-18T17:08:06.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760083/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760083/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-13","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8578, when he plans to complete the analysis of various trade scenarios on UK agriculture as part of his planning for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760084","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given on 20 September 2017, PQ UIN10048.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-09T10:40:59.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760084/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760084/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-13","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760085","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has not run any exit scheme for its UK based staff in the period from 31 March 2016 to date.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-11T16:19:32.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760085/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760085/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760086","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>​We remain concerned about restrictions on freedom of religion or belief in China and have raised this issue regularly, including at the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue which took place on 27-28 June 2017.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-09T15:38:06.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760086/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760086/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","China: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Chinese counterpart on the harassment and surveillance faced by the growing Chinese Protestant population in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","10352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760087","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The right to freedom of religion is enshrined in the Nepali Constitution of September 2015, however we are concerned that provisions around changing religion are open to interpretation. Freedom of religion or belief – particularly conversion - remains a sensitive issue. Our Embassy in Kathmandu monitors the human rights situation closely and has consistently encouraged the Government of Nepal and members of Nepal's parliament to ensure Nepal meets its international human rights obligations, this includes freedom of religion or belief, and we will continue to do so. I also raise these issues with the Nepalese Ambassador to London at a meeting on 9 October 2017.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-09T15:35:15.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760087/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760087/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the state of freedom of religion or belief in Nepal.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760088","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Our Embassy in Kathmandu has consistently encouraged the Government of Nepal and members of Nepal’s parliament to ensure Nepal meets its international human rights obligations, including freedom of religion or belief. I raised these issues with the Nepalese Ambassador to London at a meeting on 9 October 2017.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-09T15:24:38.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760088/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760088/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Government of Nepal on the state of freedom of expression in that country following the arrest of eight Christians in Charikot in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760089","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>​Our officials in Kathmandu have encouraged the Government of Nepal to implement the recommendations made by the UN Working Group on Universal Periodic Review: Nepal which includes extending an invitation to the UN special Rapporteur on Freedom of Religion or Belief. We will continue to encourage the Government of Nepal to meet its international human rights obligations.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-09T15:16:22.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760089/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760089/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: United Nations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to encourage the Government of Nepal to extend standing invitations to UN Special Procedures, including the Special Rapporteur on Freedom of Religion or Belief.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760090","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Whilst the final legislation is not yet public the draft version of the Criminal code criminalised religious conversion and the hurting of religious sentiment, which could be interpreted in a way that would limit people’s rights to express their religion and, potentially, their right to choose their religion.</p><p>During drafting our officials in Nepal met with the Ministry of Law, Justice and Parliamentary Affairs to discuss the bill and raise the need for compliance with international human rights standards. This includes ensuring the protection of the right to change religion.</p><p>I have also raised this matter in my most recent meeting with the Nepalese Ambassador to London on 9 October 2017.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-09T15:21:52.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760090/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760090/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Criminal Code Bill 2014, passed on 8 August 2017 by the Nepali Government, on freedom of religion or belief in Nepal.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760091","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Constitution of Nepal, 2015 under article 26 (1) guarantees freedom of religion as a fundamental right. Sub-article 3 states that in exercise of the right conferred by this article, one cannot do, or cause to be done, any act which may be contrary to public health, decency and morality, breach public peace, convert another person from one religion to another or any other act or conduct that may jeopardize another’s religion. These subsequent provisions may be interpreted in a way that would limit people’s rights to express their religion and, potentially, their right to choose their religion.</p><p>Our Embassy in Kathmandu has consistently encouraged the Government of Nepal and members of Nepal’s parliament to ensure Nepal meets its international human rights obligations. This includes ensuring freedom of religion or belief. I raised these issues with the Nepalese Ambassador to London at a meeting on 9 October.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-09T15:25:36.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760091/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760091/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of Article 26(3) of the Nepalese Constitution on freedom of religion or belief in Nepal.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760092","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The UK is providing £202,017 to fund a 60-strong international election observation mission for the delayed Somaliland Presidential election, now scheduled for 13 November 2017. Following a competitive tender process, the election observation team will be led by University College London.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T15:25:04.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760092/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760092/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Somaliland: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the UK will send election observers to Somaliland to observe the general election on 13 November 2017.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","10325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760093","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>​The UK plays a leading role in the fight against piracy in the Western Indian Ocean. We contribute to the Commander and Operational Headquarters of the EU's counter piracy mission, EU Navel Force (NAVFOR) Operation Atalanta. We also contribute to the Deputy Commander for the Combined Maritime Force, whose Task Force 151 has a specific focus on counter piracy. We are also a supporter of bilateral and multilateral maritime security capacity building programmes in the region. Between 2010 and 2016, the UK contributed over £17.2m to these programmes, which have helped to support counter-piracy efforts, increase regional maritime awareness and improve legal frameworks.</p><p>In May 2017, the UK hosted and co-chaired the London Somalia Conference, at which the international community reaffirmed its commitment to deterring and combatting piracy, and the Federal Government and the Federal Member States of Somalia reiterated their commitment to improving maritime security and building a capable coastguard.</p><p>According to EU NAVFOR Operation Atalanta, there have been six piracy attacks on commercial vessels in the region in 2017. Of those, only one – an attack against a Comoros flagged oil tanker, the <em>Aris 13,</em> on 13 March 2017 – was successful. By contrast, in 2011, there were 176 reported piracy attacks.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-11T16:42:06.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760093/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760093/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Somalia: Piracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce levels of maritime piracy off the Somali coast.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760094","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The UK is deeply concerned over the ability of non-governmental organisations (NGOs) to operate freely in Egypt. Ministers and senior officials regularly raise human rights concerns with Egyptian authorities; this includes restrictions on civil society. I raised these issues with Egyptian counterparts during my visit to Cairo in August 2017. The UK also raised concerns about restrictions on civil society and media freedoms in Egypt at the UN Human Rights Council in September 2017.</p><p>The UK believes that respect for individual and civil rights in Egypt is fundamental to Egyptian stability and prosperity and we will continue to urge Egypt to reduce restrictions on NGOs operating in the country, both in bilateral and multilateral fora.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T15:30:19.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760094/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760094/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Egypt: Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the ability of non-governmental organisations to operate freely in Egypt and the restrictions they face; and when and at what levels that issue was last raised by UK officials with their Egyptian counterparts.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760095","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-13","<p>We support South Korea and its allies' right to defend themselves in the face of escalating aggression from North Korea. We do not accept that there is any equivalence between the regular, defensive and legal military exercises held by South Korea and the United States, and the aggressive and illegal ballistic missile tests and nuclear testing being conducted by North Korea, which are the cause of the raised tensions on the Korean peninsula.</p><p>The UK is a sending state to the UN Command in Seoul. Alongside other nations, we routinely send military and civilian personnel to participate in two large scale military exercises conducted each year in South Korea.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-13T12:27:16.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760095/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760095/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Far East: Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect on tensions in the region of military exercises in which the UK has (a) participated and (b) not participated as a result of nuclear tests by North Korea.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760096","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>Our Ambassador to Cairo raised the dispersal of protestors in Raba'a Square with the Chair of the Egyptian Parliamentary Human Rights Committee in January. The British Government is not aware of any Egyptian accountability processes relating to the dispersal, though it is an issue to which we continue to attach importance.</p><p>Egypt is a Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) Human Rights Priority Country. FCO Ministers have asked the Egyptian authorities to take action to release journalists and political detainees who remain imprisoned, review mass judicial decisions and remove restrictions on civil society. I raised these concerns during my visit to Cairo in August. We are also deeply concerned about reports of torture and mistreatment in detention in Egypt and continue to raise these issues with the Egyptian authorities. We have raised these concerns in public, through the UN Human Rights Council and through the FCO's Human Rights Priority Country reports, and in private in meetings with Egyptian government representatives in London and in Cairo.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T15:18:17.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760096/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760096/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Egypt: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of is of progress towards identifying who was accountable for the violent dispersal of protestors in Cairo's Rab'a al-Adawiya Square on 13 August 2013; and when and at what levels that issue was last raised by UK officials with their Egyptian counterparts.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760097","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>UK officials regularly raise human rights concerns with their Egyptian counterparts. Egypt is a Foreign Office Human Rights Priority Country. Our Annual Human Rights report for 2016, which reviewed developments pertaining to human rights abuses in Egypt is available on gov.uk.</p><p>The UK raised concerns about torture, enforced disappearance and extra-judicial killings in our national statement at the UN Human Rights Council in September 2017 and Foreign Office Ministers have also publicly expressed the UK’s deep concern about the human rights situation in Egypt. We look to the Egyptian government to respect the rights guaranteed in Egypt’s constitution and investigate all reports of abuses, whether they occur in the Sinai.</p><p>We will continue to monitor the human rights situation in Egypt, and to urge the Egyptian government to implement the human rights provisions contained in its constitution.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T15:22:08.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760097/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760097/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Egypt: Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the level of assessment he has made of disappearances, mass arbitrary arrests, torture, deaths in custody and extra-judicial killings committed by the Egyptian forces in the context of their counter-terrorism operation in Sinai; and when and at what levels that issue was last raised by UK officials with their Egyptian counterparts.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>Officials have followed the case of Giulio Regeni closely since his disappearance in Cairo on 25 January 2016. We were appalled by Mr Regeni's murder, and the brutal manner of his killing. As Mr Regeni was an Italian citizen, the Italian Government is taking the lead role on his case. We have raised the need for a transparent and impartial investigation into the circumstances of Mr Regeni's murder with the Egyptian authorities at Ministerial and official levels. We are deeply concerned by the arrest of human rights lawyer Ibrahim Metwally Hegazy. The Embassy in Cairo is following up this case with the Egyptian authorities. The UK has made clear its concerns about enforced disappearances, as well as the wider human rights situation in Egypt, through its national statement at the recent session of the UN Human Rights Council.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T15:26:37.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760098/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Giulio Regeni","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of progress towards identifying who was accountable for the abduction, torture and murder of Giulio Regeni, including the arrest and continuing detention of the legal adviser to the Regeni family, Ibrahim Metwally Hagazy; and when and at what levels that issue was last raised by UK officials with their Egyptian counterparts.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","10371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>We currently have fewer than five officers working at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office that are part of the Government Commercial Function. We are therefore unable to confirm the precise numbers as this might enable individual identities to be revealed.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-10-11T16:49:13.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760099/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>​We continue to believe the two-state solution is the only viable long-term solution to the Arab Israeli conflict. We are concerned that ongoing settlement construction, incitement and terrorist attacks are undermining prospects for peace. Ultimately we believe that peace will only come through negotiations between the parties, but international action could play a role in supporting progress. We are in close consultation with international partners including the US about what kind of renewed process might have a better chance of success, including one with a greater role for regional partners.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T14:25:50.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760100/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Middle East: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to facilitate negotiations between the Israeli Government and the Palestinian Authority on peace in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","10483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760101","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>We are committed to the full implementation of the Iran nuclear deal – the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action – by all parties. Iran is in compliance with its nuclear-related commitments, as confirmed by the 31 August report of the International Atomic Energy Agency. UN Security Council Resolution 2231 calls upon Iran not to undertake any activity related to ballistic missiles designed to be capable of delivering nuclear weapons. Since July 2015, Iran has carried out a number of ballistic missile tests and has launched a space launch vehicle using such technology. This activity is not a breach of the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action. But it is inconsistent with UN Security Council Resolution 2231 and we have written to the UN Secretary General with France, Germany and the US to express our concern. We call upon Iran to refrain from such activity.</p><p>We condemn North Korea's illegal nuclear and ballistic missile programmes. We are monitoring its programme developments, as the Foreign Secretary alluded to during his remarks to Parliament on 5 September. The assessment of any links between Iran and North Korea is sensitive information. It is the long-standing policy of the Government not to comment on matters relating to intelligence or national security.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T15:32:51.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760101/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760101/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for the Iran nuclear deal of (a) ballistic missile tests carried out by Iran since July 2015 and (b) reports that Iran has provided support for the advancement of North Korea's development of nuclear weapons.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","10465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>​During drafting, our officials in Nepal met with the Ministry of Law, Justice and Parliamentary Affairs to discuss the Bill and raise the need for compliance with the international human rights standards. The final legislation is not yet public. However, if the final legislation follows up the intentions in the draft bill, I would welcome the criminalisation, within Nepali law, of acts that constitute gross violations of human rights and are established as crimes under international law, including enforced disappearances and torture.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-11T16:27:04.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760102/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: Criminal Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received on the Criminal Code Bill passed by the Nepali Parliament on 8 August 2017; what discussions he has had with Government of Nepal on that bill; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","10474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760103","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>​Our officials in Nepal met the representatives of Christian Solidarity Worldwide and Inter-faith groups in July 2016. The representatives briefed about the problem of not having adequate burial lands for religious minorities.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-11T16:24:32.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760103/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760103/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Nepal: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on limited access to burial lands of religious minority communities in Nepal.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","10473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760104","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>Public Health England (PHE) provides flu vaccines centrally for the children’s flu programme in which eligible children are offered either the nasal spray Fluenz Tetra or an inactivated flu vaccine for those children for whom Fluenz Tetra is unsuitable. Centrally purchased flu vaccines are carefully monitored by PHE to ensure there is equitable distribution across England and sufficient in-date vaccines for patients who present throughout the season.</p><p> </p><p>General practitioners and other providers are directly responsible for the flu supplies used to deliver the national flu programme to the other eligible groups. For more information on who is eligible visit:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/vaccinations/Pages/who-should-have-flu-vaccine.aspx" target="_blank">www.nhs.uk/Conditions/vaccinations/Pages/who-should-have-flu-vaccine.aspx</a></p><p>PHE maintains some oversight to help facilitate a constant supply of vaccine, liaising with vaccine manufacturers to ascertain whether there are any manufacturing problems that might affect either the number of doses available or the dates of delivery.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-10T12:44:59.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760104/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760104/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure that the NHS has an adequate supply of flu vaccines in autumn 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","10462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760105","Department of Health","false","2017-10-13","<p>Ministers have phone calls with their counterparts from the devolved administrations to discuss pertinent issues as they arise. There are no current meeting dates planned, although we would expect them to occur in due course.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-13T13:16:24.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760105/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760105/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Department of Health: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760106","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>Winter can often bring additional challenges for the National Health Service but this year planning started early and the NHS is more prepared for winter than ever before. The NHS is committed to ensuring all patients continue to receive high quality, safe and efficient care as demand over winter increases. This Government has invested an extra £6 billion into the NHS over the last two years, plus £100 million ahead of winter to ease pressures on accident and emergency departments, ensure system resilience and manage demand.</p><p> </p><p>An additional £2 billion of funding has been allocated to local authorities over the next three years, including £1 billion for 2017/18 to implement best practice in discharging patients safely and quickly to reduce delayed transfers of care.</p><p> </p><p>This year all children between 2-8 years will be offered the nasal spray vaccine to help protect them and their families against influenza.</p><p> </p><p>Influenza vaccination remains the best protection against flu, and should be offered to everyone over the age of 65 years, those who are at particular risk to flu, and pregnant women, at the earliest opportunity. Influenza vaccination should also be offered to all frontline healthcare workers through their occupational health teams.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-10T13:09:19.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760106/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760106/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Hospitals: Influenza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has emergency plans in place to assist NHS hospitals in the event of a severe influenza outbreak this year.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","10461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760107","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>The Department’s Commercial Directorate employs 43 civil servants that are part of the Government Commercial Function (GCF). Of those 43, there are nine civil servants at present that are employed through the Government Commercial Organisation.</p><p> </p><p>- 0 of the 43 members of the Commercial Department that are part of the GCF have been seconded outside Government since 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- 0 of the 43 members of the Commercial Department that are part of the GCF have been seconded in from outside Government since 2012.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-10T13:10:39.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760107/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Department of Health: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760108","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>As set out in the 2017 Drugs Strategy, the complexity and pervasiveness of drug misuse and the harms it causes means that no one department can tackle it alone. The Home Office remains the lead department for policy on drugs and implementation of the Strategy working closely with the Department of Health, Ministry of Justice and other interested Government Departments and agencies, and there are no plans to change this.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-10T12:51:26.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760108/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with the Ministry of Justice on making drugs policy a responsibility of his Department.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","10383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760109","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>No assessment has been made by the Department of the effect of mandatory identity checks on access to healthcare for homeless people.</p><p> </p><p>There is no reason why a person of no fixed abode cannot pass the ordinary resident test, as long as they meet the ordinary residence standards. Further information on these standards is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ordinary-residence-pages" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ordinary-residence-pages</a></p><p>A person will be ‘ordinarily resident’ in the United Kingdom when that residence is lawful and adopted voluntarily and for settled purposes as part of the regular order of his or her life for the time being, whether of short or long duration.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, no guidelines have been issued by the Department to hospital staff on dealing with homeless people who are seeking treatment but lack the documentation required for mandatory ID checks.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has issued guidance to general practices to clarify that proof of identity is not required to register with a general practitioner – this is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/AboutNHSservices/doctors/Pages/NHSGPs.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/AboutNHSservices/doctors/Pages/NHSGPs.aspx</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","10365","2017-10-10T15:16:02.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760109/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Health Services: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidelines his Department has issued to hospital staff on dealing with homeless people who are seeking treatment but lack the documentation required for mandatory identity checks.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","10366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760110","Department of Health","false","2017-10-09","<p>Alder Hey has appointed to only one interim role since the commencement of the management contract on 1 May, a senior communications advisor. This role was to cover a gap in capacity following the departure of the previous Director of Communications, so was not a post created by Alder Hey.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the management contract, senior roles at Liverpool Community Health Trust have been taken on by the Alder Hey Executive Team. This was not possible for the Communications post as the job holder as at 1 May was about to leave the organisation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-09T14:30:54.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760110/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Alder Hey Children's NHS Foundation Trust: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many interim posts were created by Alder Hey since that trust started managing Liverpool Community Health Trust; and what the nature of each such post was.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","10362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760111","Department of Health","false","2017-10-10","<p>No assessment has been made by the Department of the effect of mandatory identity checks on access to healthcare for homeless people.</p><p> </p><p>There is no reason why a person of no fixed abode cannot pass the ordinary resident test, as long as they meet the ordinary residence standards. Further information on these standards is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ordinary-residence-pages" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ordinary-residence-pages</a></p><p>A person will be ‘ordinarily resident’ in the United Kingdom when that residence is lawful and adopted voluntarily and for settled purposes as part of the regular order of his or her life for the time being, whether of short or long duration.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, no guidelines have been issued by the Department to hospital staff on dealing with homeless people who are seeking treatment but lack the documentation required for mandatory ID checks.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has issued guidance to general practices to clarify that proof of identity is not required to register with a general practitioner – this is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/AboutNHSservices/doctors/Pages/NHSGPs.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/AboutNHSservices/doctors/Pages/NHSGPs.aspx</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","10366","2017-10-10T15:16:02.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760111/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760111/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-13","Health Services: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of mandatory identity checks on access to healthcare for homeless people.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","10365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760112","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I<br>have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:39:27.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760112/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760112/answer","PQ10316.pdf","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760112/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-13","Oesophageal Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people have been diagnosed with oesophageal cancer aged between (a) 20 to 40, (b) 40 to 60 and (c) over 60 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760113","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Home Office had a total of 110 staff that left the Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016 to date. This was split between 59 men, at a cost of £2.8M, and 51 women at a cost of £1.98M. All Exit payments are made on the basis of length of service and final salary, which means that there is a consistent approach to the way in which exit payments are calculated.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-09T09:05:17.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760113/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760113/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Home Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) men and (b) women have left her Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760114","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>The table below provides the volume of UK passport applications from residents of the Republic of Ireland that were processed by the passport office in Belfast in each financial year from 2014/15 to 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Processed</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>9,607</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>10,343</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>10,275</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given on 7 December 2015, UIN 18581, which confirms why Her Majesty’s Passport Office is not able to provide data prior to 2014/15.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:04:28.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760114/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Passports: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications from residents of the Republic of Ireland were processed through the Belfast Passport Office in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","10355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760115","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Where radicalised young people present a threat to national security, that threat is managed by MI5 and the Police.</p><p>There are a range of powers and tools available to the police and security services to do this. The Government keeps these powers under constant review.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-10-09T14:51:21.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760115/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760115/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Radicalism: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to monitor the movements throughout the UK of young people who have become radicalised.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","10353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760116","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>This data is not collated. Information about CPS referrals and charging decisions in relation to IPCC investigations is regularly recorded manually by operational staff on an IPCC database for internal use, however the data is partial and in a number of cases CPS charging decisions remain under consideration.</p><p> </p><p>The IPCC has offered to write to the Member providing relevant management information on the issue.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-09T09:05:08.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760116/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760116/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Independent Police Complaints Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an estimate of the proportion of investigations by the Independent Police Complaints Commission that result in at least one charge being laid; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","10327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760117","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Home Office regularly engages with law enforcement bodies to review cyber crime-related legislation in order to ensure that it keeps pace with evolving threats.</p><p>Law enforcement agencies currently can and do work in close partnership with service providers to remove illegal content online.</p><p>The Home Office is not aware of any MLA requests to seize domain names and IP addresses used to facilitate cyber crime.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","10435","2017-10-09T09:05:36.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760117/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760117/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has (a) received and (b) complied with any requests under mutual legal assistance treaties requesting the seizure of domain names and IP addresses which are being used to facilitate cyber crime.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","10368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760118","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The UK Government believes that genocide should be a matter for judicial authorities to determine. However, this Government shares the House's condemnation of Daesh atrocities and led the adoption of UN Security Council Resolution 2379 with the Government of Iraq to hold Daesh to account for their crimes.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-09T15:28:18.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760118/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760118/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-13","Genocide: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government has formally recognised that Daesh has committed genocide.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","10394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760119","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Home Office regularly engages with law enforcement bodies to review cyber crime-related legislation in order to ensure that it keeps pace with evolving threats.</p><p>Law enforcement agencies currently can and do work in close partnership with service providers to remove illegal content online.</p><p>The Home Office is not aware of any MLA requests to seize domain names and IP addresses used to facilitate cyber crime.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","10368","2017-10-09T09:05:36.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760119/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760119/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has any plans to bring forward legislative proposals to enable law enforcement bodies such as the National Crime Agency (NCA) to seize domain names and IP addresses where they are being used to facilitate cyber crime; and whether she has received any representations from the NCA on that matter.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","10435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760120","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>We do not routinely comment on individual cases.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:19:31.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760120/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760120/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Entry Clearances: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made to conclude entry clearance application GWF 043559042 lodged at post in New Delhi on 4 May 2017 and received by her Department on 9 May 2017.","false","Biography information for Mike Gapes","Ilford South","Mike Gapes","10422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760121","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Currently the Home Office has 175 staff under the Government Commercial Function, of which 31 are directly employed by the Government Commercial Organisation.</p><p>There are none seconded.</p><p>2016 had 153.3 staff part of the Government Commercial Function.</p><p>Prior to that, zero because the Home Office became part of the Government Commercial Function during late 2016 having previously been autonomous.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-09T09:05:48.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760121/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760121/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Home Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many civil servants in her Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded(a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760122","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>All UKVI Decision Making Centres follow the same Customer Service Standards when handling visa entry clearance applications.</p><p> </p><p>Customer Service Standards for Settlement for those applying from outside the UK can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about-our-services" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about-our-services</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:18:00.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760122/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760122/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","UK Visas and Immigration: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department provides to the visa processing centre, Sheffield on the handling of visa entry clearance applications for a (a) spouse and (b) fiancé which have not been processed within 12 weeks; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mike Gapes","Ilford South","Mike Gapes","10432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760123","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>Documents relating to applications are dispatched to Sheffield by approved couriers who utilise specific tracking systems throughout the process. Where documents are sent directly to Sheffield they are recorded by staff upon receipt.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:14:18.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760123/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760123/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","UK Visas and Immigration: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department provides to the visa processing centre, Sheffield on the recording of (a) courier receipts and (b) tracking data for documents relating to applications for visas for entry clearance.","false","Biography information for Mike Gapes","Ilford South","Mike Gapes","10433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760124","Home Office","false","2018-07-26","<p>The former Home Secretary the Rt. Hon Amber Rudd last meeting with a Scottish Minister was in Glasgow on 27 July 2017. The Home Secretary has yet to meet with with Scottish Ministers but looks forward to doing so in due course and in line with departmental business.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-07-26T15:12:32.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760124/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760124/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Home Office: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of her Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760125","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Since November 2015 we have received notifications under section 52 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 from the following public authorities:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Police forces in England and Wales</li><li>Border Force</li><li>UK Visas and Immigration</li><li>Immigration Enforcement</li><li>National Crime Agency</li><li>Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority</li><li>Local Authorities</li></ul><p> </p><p>We have also received notifications from a range of organisations within the NHS, including NHS Trusts and General Practitioners.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-09T09:06:04.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760125/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760125/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, from which public authorities her Department has received notifications under section 52 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","10481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760126","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>As per answer of 11 September 2017, there is no specific review of the biometric process underway. UK Visas and Immigration is, however are committed to the principles of continuous improvement in all areas and to applying these to ensure processes are efficient and effective.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:13:38.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760126/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760126/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Immigration: Biometrics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8184, on immigration: biometrics, what the timetable is for that review to be completed; and if she will ensure the publication of a report setting out the findings of that review.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760127","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>The specific information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>The latest release of the asylum transparency agenda can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asylum-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asylum-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:16:45.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760127/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760127/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Asylum: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7641,  how many asylum cases had an initial decision made in the year prior to 30 June 2017 for applicants who gave a last address which was within Glasgow East constituency.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760128","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>The information you have requested is not included in statistics published by the Home Office.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:58:33.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760128/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760128/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Visas: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many visit visas issued to Malawi nationals expired unused during the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760129","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Statutory guidance is issued under section 113B(4A) of the Police Act 1997 in order to assist chief officers of police in making decisions to provide information from local police records for inclusion in enhanced DBS certificates. The first edition of this guidance was introduced on 10 September 2012 and the most recent revision came into force on 10 August 2015.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-09T09:05:56.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760129/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760129/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-13","Police: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department has issued on the disclosure of information by the police to the Disclosure and Barring Service in cases where a person has been found not guilty or no charges were brought.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","10467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760130","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>Minister of State Rory Stewart last spoke to the Scottish Government Minister for Europe and International Development in October 2017. The next meeting is expected to take place in December.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T15:41:17.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760130/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760130/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-13","Department for International Development: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of her Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760131","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>DFID joined the Government Commercial Organisation in July 2017 and currently has 11 civil servants supporting this function. None of them have been seconded outside or into the Government since this date.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T15:31:32.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760131/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760131/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-13","Department for International Development: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many civil servants in her Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760132","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>The UK is using its influence as a major shareholder to encourage the World Bank to prioritise renewable energy where this is part of a country’s least cost expansion plan, including support for clean cooking where relevant. We do so through our interventions in board discussions of the Climate Change Action Plan, the forward pipeline of projects in a country, and the design of specific projects.</p><p>We are also funding the World Bank to help developing countries with energy policy development and project implementation.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T15:30:20.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760132/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760132/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-13","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how the UK plans to (a) contribute and (b) vote at the World Bank Group (WBG) to ensure that two thirds of WBG support for energy in developing countries supports access to renewable energy and clean cooking for the world's poorest communities.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","10384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760133","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>Details of exits from the Department for International Development are routinely published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T15:25:44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760133/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760133/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-13","Department for International Development: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many (a) men and (b) women have left her Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760134","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>HMCTS can only allocate a warrant of arrest to one Approved Enforcement Agency, AEA, to execute. In the event that AEA is unable to execute the warrant there is provision to reallocate to another AEA.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T15:29:18.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760134/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760134/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Debt Collection: Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether more than one debt enforcement company can provide the warrants of arrest function in an individual case.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","10386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760135","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunal Service (HMCTS) currently uses private contractors known as Approved Enforcement Agencies (AEA) to undertake some of its enforcement functions. The work that HMCTS civilian enforcement officers do is already undertaken by these Agencies in many areas of England and Wales, where there are established links with the police. No discussions have taken place with the National Police Chiefs’ Council regarding the procurement of new AEA contracts. We will engage them and local Police Forces once we know the details of the contracts to be awarded.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-18T14:52:17.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760135/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760135/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions his Department has had with the National Police Chiefs' Council on its decision to tender the work of civilian enforcement officers.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","10434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760136","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The consultation on driving offences and penalties issued by the previous government closed on 1 February 2017. I intend to make an announcement in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T15:12:53.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760136/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760136/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Dangerous Driving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to publish the results of the consultation into offences of causing death or serious injury by dangerous driving; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","10409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760137","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-18T16:14:58.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760137/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760137/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Independent Police Complaints Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an estimate of the rate of successful prosecutions originating in investigations by the Independent Police Complaints Commission; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","10328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760138","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>Existing HMCTS contracts with Approved Enforcement Agencies (AEA) already make provision for AEAs to execute certain categories of arrest warrants. A procurement process is currently underway which will result in the establishment of new AEA contracts. That procurement process is also exploring the potential to further extend the volume of arrest warrants executed by AEAs. HMCTS will fully evaluate all proposals submitted by potential AEAs as part of the bidding process before making a final decision on this.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T15:12:14.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760138/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760138/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Debt Collection: Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment the Government has made of the ability of debt enforcement companies to fulfil the new warrants of arrest function that is being outsourced.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","10421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760139","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>On 1 April 2017, 13 members of staff from the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) left the Department to join the Government Commercial Organisation (GCO), which is part of the Cabinet Office. No members of staff were seconded outside the Government or in to Government. Prior to this date, no MoJ staff were part of the GCO.</p><p>The Government Commercial Function (GCF) is a cross-government network of around 4,000 civil servants procuring (or supporting the procurement of) goods and services for the Government. It also consists of commercial experts who support Departments in managing key commercial contracts, and planning for future commercial needs.</p><p>The GCO is formed of the 400 most senior specialists. They continue to sit within Government Departments, working on commercial contracts within those Departments, but they are available to be deployed across Government to support the most critical contracts.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-09T08:28:52.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760139/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760139/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Ministry of Justice: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760140","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-27","<p>No decision has been made yet. Should a decision to include this work be made then 139 HMCTS Civilian Enforcement Officers may be in scope to transfer to a new service provider under TUPE (Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations 2006) if it applies.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-27T18:05:44.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760140/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760140/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has made an estimate of the potential number of civilian enforcement officers who will transfer to the private sector as a result of its decision to outsource the work of such officers.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","10415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760141","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The information requested is set out in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>The average time (weeks) from receipt in HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service to outcome for Personal Independence Payment (PIP)<sup>1 </sup>Appeals<sup>2</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong><strong><sup>3</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Greenock venue<sup>4</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Scotland</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Qtr 1 2017/18</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes</p><p><sup>1 </sup>PIP (New Claim Appeals), which replaced Disability Living Allowance (DLA), from 8 April 2013, also includes Personal Independence Claims (Reassessments).</p><p><sup>2 </sup>Appeals includes those cleared with and without a tribunal hearing. They may include time spent at the Upper Tribunal.</p><p><sup>3</sup> Full financial years April to March; Quarter 1 April to June 2017.</p><p><sup>4</sup> Data on SSCS cases are attributed to the hearing venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. For those living in Inverclyde this is the Greenock Venue</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data that are available.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T15:14:07.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760141/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760141/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Personal Independence Payment: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average waiting time is for an appeal against a mandatory reconsideration of a decision on personal independence payments in (a) Inverclyde and (b) Scotland for the last four periods for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","10426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760142","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-10","<p>Since the general election on 8 June 2017, the following meetings have taken place between ministers from the Ministry of Justice and counterparts in the devolved administrations:</p><ul><li><p>Telephone meeting between the Secretary of State for Justice and the First Minister for Wales on 22 June 2017</p></li><li><p>Telephone meeting between Minister Gyimah and the Cabinet Secretary for Communities and Children in the Welsh Government, on 6 July 2017</p></li><li><p>Telephone meeting between the Secretary of State for Justice and the Cabinet Secretary for Justice in Scotland on 23 August 2017.</p></li><li><p>Meeting between the Secretary of State for Justice and the First Minister of Wales on 18 September 2017 in Cardiff.</p><p> </p></li></ul><p>Dr Lee, is due to meet Cabinet Secretary for Communities and Children in the Welsh Government, in Cardiff on 30 November 2017.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-10T15:22:56.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760142/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760142/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-13","Ministry of Justice: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760143","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The number of staff in my Department who have received a pay increase above, at, or less than 1% in 2015-16 is shown in the table below.</p><p>To collate a response for years 2013/2014 and 2014/2015 would exceed the cost limit.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Increase in basic salary 2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1% increase</p></td><td><p>86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater than 1%</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>89</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This response covers only Home Civil Servants (HCS) staff employed directly by my department; it does not include staff seconded from the Northern Ireland Civil Service (NICS) who remain on NICS terms and conditions, including pay.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-09T14:48:52.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760143/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760143/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-13","Northern Ireland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above one per cent, (b) at one per cent and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760144","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>No Civil Servants in my Department are part of the Government Commercial Function.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-09T14:49:52.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760144/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760144/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-13","Northern Ireland Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760145","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-11-16","<p>Earlier this year, in recognition of the unique circumstances in Northern Ireland, the UK Government made clear that it was prepared to make available additional financial support following the confidence and supply agreement between the Conservative Party and the Democratic Unionist Party.</p><p> </p><p>That agreement made clear our desire to see the money decided upon and spent by a restored Executive for the benefit of all in Northern Ireland. In the meantime, though, we acknowledge that Northern Ireland’s unique circumstances cannot simply be ignored, especially given the pressures that we have seen in the continued absence of an Executive.</p><p> </p><p>That is why I announced during the Second Reading of the Northern Ireland Budget Bill on 13 November our commitment to make available £50m from the Confidence and Supply Agreement for addressing immediate health and education pressures in the 2017/18 financial year. If the Northern Ireland administration confirm that they would access this in 2017/18, that funding would form part of the Supplementary Estimates process in the New Year and be subject to the full authorisation of the House of Commons.</p><p />","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-11-16T12:36:01.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760145/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760145/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760145/answer/previousversion/13527","Biography information for James Brokenshire","21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-13","Health Services: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the timescale is for allocating the additional funding for health as part of the Government's agreement with the Democratic Unionist Party in the absence of the Northern Ireland Executive.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","10356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760146","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>From 1 April 2016, only one individual left under an exit scheme. Due to the risk of identification their gender cannot be disclosed.</p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-09T14:50:43.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760146/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760146/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-13","Northern Ireland Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760147","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Scotland Office does not run its own staff exit scheme. Any departures would be under schemes run by the parent employers of staff who join the office on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the small numbers involved, specific details and costs cannot be provided to protect the privacy and identity of individuals concerned.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-09T14:24:34.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760147/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760147/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-13","Scotland Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760148","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Scotland Office has no current or previous staff that are part of the Government Commercial Function.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-09T14:25:29.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760148/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760148/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-13","Scotland Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760149","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. Staff that join do so on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government. Matters such as pay awards would be a matter for the employing departments.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-09T14:23:03.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760149/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760149/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-13","Scotland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above one per cent, (b) at one per cent and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760150","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>Departmental pay awards have been applied in accordance with HMT pay guidance that restricts increases to an average of one per cent across all staff. Over the last three years, the department has linked pay awards to end of year performance marks, differentiating the award based on these marks.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of employees who received a pay increase a) above, (b) at and (c) less than one per cent for each of the last three years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Pay Award Year</p></td><td><p>Above 1%</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>Below 1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>8881</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>4821</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>10551</p></td><td><p>34</p></td><td><p>2641</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>9230</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>4706</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures include staff in post on the 1<sup>st</sup> August each year who were eligible for a pay award. Figures for 2017/18 are not available as the pay award has not yet been implemented.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T09:57:08.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760150/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760150/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above one per cent, (b) at one per cent and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760151","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The financial consequences of the proposed transfer of the Valley Lines are still being discussed between the two governments.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T11:01:22.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760151/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760151/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the proposed transfer Valley Lines to the Welsh Government for the (a) Welsh Block Grant and (b) use of the Barnett Formula.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760152","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Insurance costs relating to the Cardiff Valley Lines subsequent to their proposed transfer would be a matter for the Welsh Government.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T11:04:38.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760152/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760152/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on insurance costs of the proposed transfer of Valley Lines to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760153","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>In developing its detailed proposals for the proposed transfer of ownership of the Cardiff Valley Lines, licensing issues relating to the assets are a matter for the Welsh Government and the Office of Rail and Road.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:31:41.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760153/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760153/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of licensing issues surrounding the proposed transfer of Network Rail's assets of Valley Lines to the Welsh Government and the future maintenance of those assets.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760154","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>As the employer, Network Rail is responsible for ensuring the protection of the rights of such employees who are affected by the proposed transfer of the Cardiff Valley Lines. It is absolutely right that all parties involved in any such transfer place the protection of affected staff at the centre of their thinking in developing the detailed proposals for a transfer.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:54:51.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760154/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760154/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the transfer of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government on the Network Rail workforce who maintain and operate the Valley Lines.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760155","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Network Rail does not employ staff to work solely on the Valley Lines, which is not accounted for as a business unit. The Valley Lines are supported by staff in Network Rail’s Route business (based in Cardiff) as well as centralised functions based elsewhere in the UK.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:43:11.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760155/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760155/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people are employed by Network Rail to work on the Valley Lines.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760156","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>Department for Transport’s Central department and its Executive Agencies have 223 civil servants who fall into the definition of Government Commercial Function. DfT holds central records of inward secondees but not the activities they undertake. However, we are aware of 3 individuals currently seconded into DfT from British Transport Police, Network Rail and Transport for London.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T10:07:52.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760156/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760156/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Department for Transport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760157","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>Volkswagen UK provided the Department with the following figures for the number of ‘fixes’ that have been applied to the affected UK vehicles, across the Group:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of vehicles reported ‘fixed’ on:</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17 August 2017</p></td><td><p>7 September 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Audi</p></td><td><p>273,483</p></td><td><p>277,388</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SEAT</p></td><td><p>42,871</p></td><td><p>43,674</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Skoda</p></td><td><p>58,807</p></td><td><p>62,763</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>VW commercial vehicles</p></td><td><p>37,599</p></td><td><p>38,467</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>VW passenger cars</p></td><td><p>351,203</p></td><td><p>355,208</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>763,963</p></td><td><p>777,500</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-12T11:56:26.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760157/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760157/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2017 to Question 4255, on Volkswagen, how many (a) Audis, (b) SEATs, (c) Skodas, (d) Volkswagen commercial vehicles and (e) Volkswagen private cars had had fixes applied by the time of the (i) August and (ii) September meetings.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","10431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760158","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>In December 2016 my Department introduced a requirement that future rail franchises have better mobile connectivity for passengers. This significantly increases the number of places along the railway line where there is signal. There are three railway franchises in the South West. For Great Western and Cross Country Franchises these requirements will come into effect in 2019 and must be implemented no later than 2022. The procurement of the South Western Franchise started prior to the requirement in December 2016, but they have agreed to voluntarily adopt this approach.</p><p>My Department is working closely with the Department of Digital, Culture Media and Sport (DCMS) to see what further improvements can be made to mobile connectivity on trains.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-12T12:10:57.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760158/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760158/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to increase mobile telephone coverage alongside inter-city rail networks throughout the South West to improve on-board connectivity.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","10427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760159","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State met with Ken Skates AM, Cabinet Secretary for Economy and Infrastructure on 7<sup>th</sup> September this year. The pair are due to meet again on 16<sup>th</sup> October. The Secretary of State also met with Keith Brown MSP, Cabinet Secretary for Economy, Jobs and Fair Work on 3rd July.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-12T10:56:19.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760159/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760159/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Department for Transport: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760160","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>Operator licensing is an important regime to ensure haulage and bus operators act responsibly, safely and legally, and it is already contained within UK law. Leaving the EU will give the UK control over our Operator Licensing regime.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-12T11:54:34.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760160/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760160/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Transport: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will undertake to assess the effectiveness of directives on operator licensing after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","10471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760161","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department remains committed to supporting community transport operators. The Department will carry out a public consultation later this autumn, which will set out the changes needed to the guidance on the issue and use of permits.</p><p> </p><p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation. It would be inappropriate to speculate as to any legislative action which the government may take when the exit negotiations are concluded, for the purpose of implementing the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-12T16:41:12.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760161/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760161/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Community Transport: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will take steps to protect and widen derogations for community transport operators to operate vehicles under a Section 19 or 22 permit after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","10472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760162","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government is in favour of reducing waste at source and supports efforts in the cruise ship sector to reduce, reuse and recycle waste.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to work closely and have discussions with cruise industry officials both domestically, within the European Sustainable Shipping Forum, as well as at the International Maritime Organisation.</p><p>These discussions will focus on improving and enhancing the control of ship generated waste.</p><p> </p><p>Discussions concerning the amount of cruise ship generated waste that is deposited in harbours and ports is best led by the industry in the first instance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T13:25:59.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760162/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760162/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Passenger Ships: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will hold discussions with cruise ship operators on reducing the amount of waste generated by cruise ships that is deposited in harbours and ports.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760163","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The UK’s harbours and ports have an excellent safety record but we must never be complacent.</p><p> </p><p>The Department provides comprehensive guidance to ports, harbours and terminals to assist them in their duty to manage safety in their areas through the Port Marine Safety Code and related Guide to Good Practice.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T13:28:04.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760163/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760163/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Shipping: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of navigational accidents in harbours and ports.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760164","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The 2015 Spending Review established a funding envelope for Phase Two of £28.55bn (in 2015 prices). Following the transfer of scope of Crewe Tunnel between Phase 2a and Phase 2b, total funding of £25.07bn has been allocated to Phase 2b (including provision for rolling stock). HS2 Ltd is expected to manage all elements of the delivery of Phase 2b from within the overall funding provision. As such, there is no separately designated funding for the section of track running through the Eddisbury constituency.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-12T11:39:46.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760164/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760164/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much and what proportion of the funding available to the second phase of High Speed 2 has been allocated to the section of the track running through Eddisbury constituency.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","10333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760165","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>There are a number of investments to increase the overall capacity and improve journey times between Hull and Liverpool via Leeds.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2014, faster services with a 15 minute journey time saving began running between Liverpool Lime Street and Manchester Victoria.</p><p>In 2015, longer trains started and in October of this year, we will have completed building an additional platform and track on this route to allow fast trains to pass slow trains.</p><p> </p><p>We are also rebuilding Liverpool Lime Street to enable more and longer trains to serve that station, with three services a day to Scotland from December 2018 and extra trains to Manchester and Bradford by December 2019.</p><p>Network Rail are currently on site to improve the track, reducing journey time savings on the section between Manchester and Stalybridge by May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Additional through trains will run between Manchester and Leeds from 2018, with new build 5 carriage trains starting to replace the 3-car trains currently in operation.</p><p> </p><p>Northern and TransPennine Express, will deliver brand new trains, totalling more than 500 new carriages. All existing trains will be refurbished, many more of the trains to Hull from Manchester will be doubled in capacity, and all the out-dated Pacer trains will be withdrawn from service. In total there will be room for 40,000 extra passengers and more than 2,000 extra services a week across all of the North.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","10331","2017-10-12T13:21:00.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760165/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760165/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Railways: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has plans to increase passenger capacity on trains between Hull and (a) Liverpool and (b) Leeds; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","10330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760166","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>There are a number of investments to increase the overall capacity and improve journey times between Hull and Liverpool via Leeds.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2014, faster services with a 15 minute journey time saving began running between Liverpool Lime Street and Manchester Victoria.</p><p>In 2015, longer trains started and in October of this year, we will have completed building an additional platform and track on this route to allow fast trains to pass slow trains.</p><p> </p><p>We are also rebuilding Liverpool Lime Street to enable more and longer trains to serve that station, with three services a day to Scotland from December 2018 and extra trains to Manchester and Bradford by December 2019.</p><p>Network Rail are currently on site to improve the track, reducing journey time savings on the section between Manchester and Stalybridge by May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Additional through trains will run between Manchester and Leeds from 2018, with new build 5 carriage trains starting to replace the 3-car trains currently in operation.</p><p> </p><p>Northern and TransPennine Express, will deliver brand new trains, totalling more than 500 new carriages. All existing trains will be refurbished, many more of the trains to Hull from Manchester will be doubled in capacity, and all the out-dated Pacer trains will be withdrawn from service. In total there will be room for 40,000 extra passengers and more than 2,000 extra services a week across all of the North.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","10330","2017-10-12T13:21:00.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760166/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760166/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Railways: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has plans to reduce train journey times between Hull and (a) Liverpool and (b) Leeds; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","10331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760167","Wales Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Wales Office received rental income from the Welsh Government in 2011-12 and 2012-13, and the Greater London Lieutenancy from 2013-14 to 2016-17.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-10-09T11:47:20.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760167/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760167/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-13","Wales Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8748, on Wales Office: buildings, if he will list the people and organisations from whom that rental income was derived.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760168","Wales Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>No staff working at the Wales Office have left under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-10-09T11:48:31.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760168/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760168/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-13","Wales Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760169","Wales Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>There are no staff at the Wales Office who are part of the Government Commercial Function.</p><p>The Wales Office obtains any commercial expertise required from the Ministry of Justice or Crown Commercial Services.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-10-09T11:49:22.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760169/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760169/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-13","Wales Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760170","Wales Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>Wales Office staff employed by the Ministry of Justice who have received a pay increase above, at or less than, 1% in the last three years is shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Percentage Salary Increase: Wales Office</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Less than 1%</strong></p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1%</strong></p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Greater than 1%</strong></p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Excluded</strong></p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>36</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>35</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>37</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>~ </strong>Figure omitted to avoid disclosure of totals of 2 or fewer</p><p><strong>* </strong>Figure omitted to ensure other data cannot be derived</p><p> </p><p>Data is not available for Wales Office staff employed by organisations theory other than the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-10-09T12:07:04.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760170/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760170/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-13","Wales Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above one per cent, (b) at one per cent and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760171","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-09","<p>No one has left the Government Equalities Office under an exit scheme since 31 March 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","10351","2017-10-09T18:01:22.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760171/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760171/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-09-13","Government Equalities Office: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many (a) men and (b) women have left the Government Equalities Office under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760172","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-09","<p>No one has left the Government Equalities Office under an exit scheme since 31 March 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","10337","2017-10-09T18:01:22.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760172/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760172/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-09-13","Government Equalities Office: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what amount has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left the Government Equalities Office under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760173","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-09","<p>Employment discrimination on grounds of nationality is in most cases prohibited by the Equality Act 2010 and will remain so, but the provisions in the Act do not distinguish between EU and non-EU nationals, nor between British and non-British EU nationals, and statistics in this area do not allow these distinctions to be made.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Equalities Office sponsors the Equality and Human Rights Commission, which has powers to enforce the Equality Act 2010 in cases where it suspects unlawful discrimination in employment may have occurred.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-09T07:30:11.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760173/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760173/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-09-13","Migrant Workers: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment her Department has made of the levels of discrimination against EU citizens in the UK in relation to (a) employment and (b) redundancy since June 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760174","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The available information for Housing Benefit claims with removal of the spare room subsidy reduction, including average amount deducted, is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/housing-benefit-caseload-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/housing-benefit-caseload-statistics</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T16:26:12.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760174/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760174/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an estimate of the average amount deducted from housing benefit claimants in (a) Scotland, (b) England, (c) Wales and (d) Great Britain due to the removal of the spare room subsidy in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760175","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>Invitations to meet with third sector organisations are routinely considered by Ministers on a case by case basis.</p><p> </p><p>At departmental level officials from the DWP have regular meetings with Scottish stakeholders, including representatives from third sector organisations, to discuss matters including the roll out of Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the formal implementation planning for Universal Credit there are a range of external engagement activities for each Local Authority area tailored to the individual locality.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-11T15:38:47.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760175/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760175/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Universal Credit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet representatives of the Scottish third sector to discuss the roll-out of universal credit in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","10387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760176","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>During the period 1 April 2016 to 15 September 2017, a total of 2,797 people have exited the Department for Work and Pensions, via Voluntary Exit, Voluntary and Compulsory Redundancy Schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not maintain exit scheme records relating to gender.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T16:22:00.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760176/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760176/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760177","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>DWP participates in the Government Commercial Organisation (GCO) scheme.</p><p>32 Civil Servants have transferred to the GCO from DWP. No one that has transferred onto the GCO has been seconded outside the Government, or have come in on a secondment.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T17:38:06.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760177/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760177/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside the Government and (b) in from outside the Government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760178","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The table below lists the most recent meetings between Ministers from his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations and the next planned meetings.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Minister</p></td><td><p>Devolved Administration</p></td><td><p>Date of most recent meeting</p></td><td><p>Next planned meeting</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Secretary of State for Work and Pensions</p></td><td><p>Scottish Government</p></td><td><p>14 September 2017</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minister for Employment</p></td><td><p>Welsh Government</p></td><td><p>13 July 2017</p></td><td><p>Provisional 27 November 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minister for Disabled People, Work and Health</p></td><td><p>Scottish Government</p></td><td><p>25 October 2016</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-09T16:33:03.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760178/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760178/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760179","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>Ministerial visits have been routinely published as transparency data on Gov.uk: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-ministers-hospitality-and-gifts#history" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-ministers-hospitality-and-gifts#history</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-09T17:18:34.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760179/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760179/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8068, on food banks: domestic visits, whether Ministers of his Department have visited a food bank in Scotland since May 2010.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760180","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>The wording of the key performance indicator was set out in the reply to Freedom of Information request 1740, that the honourable lady referred to. It is not provided to decision makers at either the initial decision or mandatory reconsideration stages.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-10-11T15:52:03.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760180/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760180/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the DWP response to FOI request 1740 on key performance indicators, if he will set out the wording of the key performance indicator referred to in the FOI response; and whether that the key performance indicator is provided to officials (a) taking initial decisions on benefit claims and (b) conducting mandatory reconsiderations.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","10482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760181","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>In 1996 the Australia Nuclear Science and Technology Organisation (ANSTO) signed a contract with the United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority (UKAEA) for the processing of spent nuclear fuel from the Australian research reactor at the Dounreay reprocessing facility. The contract contained an obligation to return uranium and an option to return waste which is supported by a MoU between the UK and Australian Governments in the form of an intergovernmental letter. The radioactive waste, which arose from the processing, comprises several tens of drums of cemented waste. The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) assumed responsibility for the material when it became owners of Dounreay in 2005.</p><p> </p><p>Cemented waste is challenging in terms of transport and volume, and for the ANSTO waste the return would require multiple moves or the provision of new flasks to ensure transport can be secured. The Scottish and UK Governments consulted on a proposed policy of radioactive waste substitution for the radioactive waste arising from historic fuel reprocessing contracts with overseas customers at Dounreay in 2010. Agreement was reached between the Scottish and UK Governments on 16 March 2012. Waste substitution is an internationally accepted practice where a radiological equivalent amount of waste is returned to the customer in a form that is acceptable. A contract was signed in 2014 with the NDA to enable waste substitution.</p><p> </p><p>The substituted radioactive waste will be in the form of four vitrified residue containers holding waste which falls within the activity levels of Intermediate Level Waste. The vitrified residue (sealing of radioactive waste in molten glass poured into engineered stainless steel containers) comes from Sellafield. Waste in this form is immobilised. The cemented drums containing the Australian-origin radioactive waste from the processing of the spent nuclear fuel will be retained and managed at Dounreay pending final disposal, as the Dounreay Intermediate Level Waste stores are designed to accept it.</p><p> </p><p>The vitrified residues are forecast to be returned to Australia by 2022 and are expected to be stored in an authorised storage facility located at Lucas Heights near Sydney, where the Australian research reactor is located. Following storage at Lucas Heights the vitrified residues will be co-located with a new disposal facility for Low Level Waste and will be temporary stored at that facility.</p><p> </p><p>The Australian Government accepts that it has an international obligation to receive the vitrified residues. The Department of Industry, Innovation and Science (DIIS) is charged with identifying a site – National Radioactive Waste Management Facility – for its Low Level Waste currently stored in 100 different places around Australia. The NDA has been informed that following a public consultation process across Australia, DIIS is now actively engaged in dialogue with two communities in South Australia – Wallerberdina Station, near Hawker, and at Kimba. A decision on where the facility will be located has not yet been made.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-10-12T14:01:25.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760181/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760181/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Radioactive Waste: Australia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the total volume of UK-generated radioactive waste that will be sent to Australia's proposed national radioactive waste facility; what the origins are of the waste that will be returned to Australia for disposal in that facility; and what the level of radioactivity is of all the waste that will be sent to that facility.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","10476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760182","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is committed to tackling climate change and to the Paris Agreement.</p><p>We have been among the most successful countries in the developed world in growing our economy while reducing emissions. Since 1990, we have cut emissions by more than 40 per cent while our economy has grown by two thirds. This is the best performance amongst G7 nations. PWC has recently found the UK is leading the G20 in clean growth, decarbonising faster than any other country.</p><p>This year the Government has announced a number of policy measures to support low carbon transition including: confirmation of the phase out of unabated coal power generation in Great Britain by 2025; new measures to support green finance; and £246 million for the ‘Faraday Challenge’ to support the design, development and manufacture of electric vehicles. We have held a Contracts for Difference auction which resulted in the cost of new offshore wind projects from 2022-23 being 50% lower than the first auction held in 2015. We will publish our Clean Growth Strategy shortly which will set out how we will reduce emissions through the 2020s.</p><p>The Government is working internationally to support implementation of the Paris Agreement. We actively participate in the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change negotiations to agree detailed rules that will underpin the Paris Agreement. We are working closely with EU partners to agree the legislative package that will set out how the EU will meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement. The International Climate Fund of £5.8bn between 2016-2020 is helping to unlock investment in developing countries and raise ambition; and through our foreign policy network the UK is engaging countries around the world on delivery of their Nationally Determined Contributions under the Paris Agreement.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-09T16:32:41.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760182/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760182/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps the Government has taken to support the implementation of the Paris Agreement on climate change.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","10428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760183","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>Twelve civil servants in the department are professionally part of the Government Commercial Function with two of those being employed by the Government Commercial Organisation. (a) Nil return. (b) Nil return.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T10:59:19.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760183/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760183/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many civil servants in his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been seconded (a) outside Government and (b) in from outside the government in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760184","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>In core BEIS, 99 men and 66 women have left the Department or former constituent Departments under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T10:58:27.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760184/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760184/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department or former constituent Departments under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760185","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>Ministers in the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy regularly discuss matters of mutual interest with their counterparts in the devolved administrations.</p><p>The most recent meetings took place on 7 September 2017 when my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and my hon. Friend the Minister for Climate Change and Industry met with both Ken Skates AM, Cabinet Secretary for Economy and Infrastructure in the Welsh Government and with Paul Wheelhouse MSP, Minister for Business, Innovation and Energy in the Scottish Government. There are currently no Northern Ireland Executive Ministers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T11:00:24.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760185/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760185/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers from his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760186","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-10","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State and Ministers in the Department found it extremely valuable to meet businesses from across Scotland when they last visited. Subject to Parliamentary business, we look forward to visiting again in the future.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-10T12:49:17.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760186/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760186/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 7643, if he or a Minister of his Department will undertake to visit a company headquartered in Glasgow East constituency in 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760187","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>Toshiba is seeking to sell NuGen, the developer of the proposed Moorside nuclear plant, in a private commercial transaction. We engage regularly with developers on a range of topics, including financing, though the details of these discussions are commercially confidential.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-10-12T13:58:06.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760187/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760187/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Nuclear Power Stations: Sellafield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to secure funding for the development of a nuclear plant at Moorside in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Trudy Harrison","Copeland","Trudy Harrison","10357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760188","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>As I stated in the answer to Question UIN 10360, there are approximately 33,000 Scottish Limited Partnerships (SLPs) registered with Companies House. All registered SLPs are eligible under the terms of the Scottish Partnerships (Register of People with Significant Control) Regulations 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The above regulations also require a Scottish qualifying partnership (SQP) to register with Companies House and deliver information concerning its People with Significant Control (PSC). An SQP is a general partnership constituted under the law of Scotland that is a qualifying partnership under the Partnership (Accounts) Regulations 2008. As of 22 September 2017, 493 SQPs have delivered PSC information to Companies House.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:04:51.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760188/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760188/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Scottish Limited Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Scottish limited partnerships are qualifying under the terms of the Scottish Partnerships (Register of People with Significant Control) Regulations 2017 and the Companies and Partnerships (Accounts and Audit) Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","10329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760189","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>There are approximately 33,000 Scottish Limited Partnerships (SLPs) registered with Companies House. All registered SLPs are eligible under the terms of the Scottish Partnerships (Register of People with Significant Control) Regulations 2017.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-09T16:39:23.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760189/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760189/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-13","Scottish Limited Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Scottish limited partnerships are eligible under the terms of the Scottish Partnerships (Register of People with Significant Control) Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","10360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760190","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-09","<p>As set out by the Prime Minister in her Florence speech on 22 September, the UK will seek to agree a time-limited interim period with the EU.</p><p>The UK would intend to pursue new trade negotiations with others during the interim period, having left the EU. The UK would not bring into effect any new arrangements with third countries, which were not consistent with the terms of the interim agreement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-09T16:26:00.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760190/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760190/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-13","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, when trade negotiations with other countries will commence after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760191","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-09","<p>The UK Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU Free Trade Agreements (FTAs) or other EU preferential arrangements.</p><p>The Government is seeking to transition into UK law, the trade agreements that the EU has with other countries and to which we are a party. There are around 40 existing EU FTAs. This will be a technical exercise, to ensure minimal disruption to business, consumers and workers alike.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-09T16:01:32.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760191/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760191/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-13","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many trade agreements with other countries will need to be renegotiated after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760192","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-09","<p>We are talking to a broad range of countries about future trading relationships. Through these discussions, we will aim to put in place various mechanisms, to improve trading relations and remove barriers affecting UK businesses. However, the length of time to complete a specific trade agreement negotiation can vary significantly, therefore, at this stage, we cannot say specifically when agreements could be reached.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-09T14:42:09.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760192/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760192/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-13","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the length of time it will take to conclude trade negotiations with other countries after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760193","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-11","<p>I refer the hon Member for Hemsworth to the answer I gave on 12 September, UIN: 10040.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-11T12:52:43.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760193/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760193/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-13","Department for International Trade: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since its creation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760194","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-10","<p>DIT Ministers and officials engage with the Devolved Administrations in a variety of ways, including having given evidence to the Scottish Parliament’s Culture, Tourism, Europe and External Relations Committee. We will continue to engage closely with the Devolved Administrations in the future to support trade and investment across the UK.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-10T09:47:39.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760194/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760194/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-13","Department for International Trade: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the dates were of the most recent meetings between Ministers of his Department and their counterparts in the devolved administrations; and what the dates are of the next planned meetings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","10403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760195","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not have an internal commercial team and therefore does not have any Civil Servants in the Department who are part of the Government Commercial Function. The Department uses a commercial shared service function to carry out commercial activity on its behalf. This function is supplied by the Department for International Trade.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-09T16:43:09.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760195/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760195/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","Department for Exiting the European Union: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants of his Department are part of the Government Commercial Function; and how many of those civil servants have been (a) seconded outside of government and (b) seconded in from outside of government since his Department was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760196","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has not run any exit schemes since its creation.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-09T16:40:47.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760196/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760196/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","Department for Exiting the European Union: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many (a) men and (b) women have left his Department under exit schemes since its creation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760197","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-09","<p>The UK has a longstanding tradition of ensuring our rights and liberties are protected domestically and of fulfilling our international human rights obligations. The Charter of Fundamental Rights (the Charter) only applies to Member States when acting within the scope of EU law. The Charter did not create any new rights. Instead it was intended to catalogue the rights that already existed in EU law, and the bill sets out how this underlying law is being converted into UK law at the point we exit the EU. Therefore it is no longer appropriate, nor will it make sense in the context of the UK's exit from the EU, to retain the Charter in UK law.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-09T09:20:53.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760197/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760197/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","Charter of Fundamental Rights (EU)","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, for what reason his policy of incorporating EU law into UK law excludes the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760198","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-19","<p>We will pursue a deep and special partnership with the EU taking in both economic and security cooperation. As a priority we will seek a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement that is of greater scope and ambition than any such existing agreement.</p><p>As we have made clear in our future partnership paper, we believe the UK and EU should continue to consult each other on foreign and security policy issues and agree joint positions, so that we can speak out together and drive progress on areas in our mutual interest. As an example, we should look to coordinate action, and share information, on sanctions policy when needed in order to respond robustly to those who challenge the rules-based international order, as we have recently done effectively in the case of Russia and Iran. We are clear that we want the EU to succeed: a successful EU, with the UK as its closest partner, is in all of our shared interests.</p><p>We want to have the greatest possible tariff- and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours, as well as to negotiate our own trade agreements around the world. We want to ensure that UK companies have the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within European markets – and to let European businesses do the same in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-19T11:04:36.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760198/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760198/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","UK relations with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the (a) economic, (b) diplomatic and (c) tariff conditions that would apply to relations between the UK and the EU as a result of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760199","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-12","<p>As set out in our position paper on Northern Ireland and Ireland, the UK Government, Irish Government, and European Union all agree on maintaining the Common Travel Area. In our position paper, the UK provided clear assurance that the CTA can continue to operate in its current form and can do so without compromising in any way Ireland’s ability to honour its obligations as an EU Member State, including in relation to free movement for EEA nationals in Ireland. If the EU wishes, the UK would be content for such an assurance to be reflected in the Withdrawal Agreement. Michel Barnier has confirmed the EU’s commitment towards maintaining the Common Travel Area, and the UK and EU have started drafting common principles.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-12T15:00:05.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760199/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760199/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-13","Common Travel Area","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to his oral contribution of 7 September 2017, Official Report, column 302, what the evidential basis is for the statement that the EU Commission no longer believe that continuing with the Common Travel Area after the UK leaves the EU would impinge on EU citizens' rights.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760201","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>I welcome the report by the RNIB on the experiences of blind and partially sighted people<br>at the 2017 General Election. The Government will consider these recommendations as<br>part of our current Call for Evidence on the experience of disabled people in registering to<br>vote and voting and will look at the evidence as a whole in planning how to take forward<br>any changes.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-20T14:52:54.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760201/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760201/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-13","General Election 2017","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the findings of the report, Turned Out 2017, published by the RNIB on problems experienced by blind and partially sighted voters at the 2017 General Election; and if he will implement that report's recommendations before local authority elections take place in 2018.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","105016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760202","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department’s <em>Transport Investment Strategy </em>recognises that high performing infrastructure can drive economic growth across the country. To inform our decisions about future investment in the strategic road network, Highways England’s 18 route strategies and strategic economic growth plan, published in March, have assessed how the performance of all parts of the network, including the A19 through Easington, can promote growth.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-12T13:29:59.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760202/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760202/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-13","Economic Growth: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will make an assessment of the value of the A19 to the promotion of economic growth and regeneration in Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","105017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760203","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Treasury ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. This includes regular meetings with the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Government transferred the regulation of consumer credit to the FCA in 2014. The Government welcomes the ongoing work of the FCA to review the high-cost credit market, including the rent-to-own sector. The Chancellor will not be making a statement at this time.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","105021","2017-10-09T15:48:20.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760203/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760203/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Instalment Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations his Department has received on rent-to-own goods; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","105020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760204","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>There are numerous public funds that go towards supporting the automotive sector, including research and development, regional growth funds, local growth funds and skills funding. We do not collect data on overall spending by region.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-09T15:45:34.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760204/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760204/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding the Government has (a) given and (b) undertaken to provide to car manufacturers in each region of the UK in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","105038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760205","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Spring Budget 2017 announced a £435m package to support businesses facing the steepest increases in business rates bills following the revaluation, which included a £1,000 business rates discount for pubs with a rateable value of up to £100,000 for 1 year from April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, pubs could benefit from the £110m support for small businesses and £300m for local authorities to support individual hard cases in their local area. This is on top of the £3.6bn transitional relief scheme and cuts in business rates announced at Budget 2016 costing nearly £9bn over the next five years.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T13:03:12.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760205/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760205/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Public Houses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has assessed the potential merits of increasing annual business rates relief for pubs.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","105063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760206","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has published Advance Thin Capitalisation Agreement (ATCA) statistics to 2016/17, as part of a wider publication of data relating to HMRC’s work on collecting tax owed to the UK. This is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635330/Transfer_Pricing_and_Diverted_Profits_Tax_statistics.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635330/Transfer_Pricing_and_Diverted_Profits_Tax_statistics.pdf</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T15:07:15.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760206/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760206/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Advance Pricing Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 70304, how many Advance Thin Capitalisation agreements were made in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17; how long it took to reach each such agreement; how many such agreements are still in force; how many intra-group company bodies those agreements apply to; and what the average level of taxable profits was for those agreements.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","10489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760207","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Due to the June Election, Queen’s Speech and Ministerial and Select Committee appointments, the Government’s response to this report has been rescheduled and will be laid before Parliament (as Treasury Minutes) on 19 October 2017.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T13:01:28.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760207/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760207/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-13","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Government plans to respond to the Public Accounts Committee report on the HM Revenue and Customs Estate, published on 28 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","10496"
