"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759561","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-20","<p>We want to see the financial support for Northern Ireland decided upon and spent by a devolved government to benefit the whole community. No funding has been allocated to date.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government receives regular representations from departments of the Northern Ireland Executive on a range of matters of importance to Northern Ireland and the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL1532 ; HL1533","2017-09-20T10:36:25.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759561/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759561/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much of the £1 billion additional funding for Northern Ireland agreed in June has been allocated to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL1531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759562","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-20","<p>We want to see the financial support for Northern Ireland decided upon and spent by a devolved government to benefit the whole community. No funding has been allocated to date.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government receives regular representations from departments of the Northern Ireland Executive on a range of matters of importance to Northern Ireland and the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL1531 ; HL1533","2017-09-20T10:36:25.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759562/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759562/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what requests they have received from departments of the Northern Ireland Executive for the £1 billion additional funding for Northern Ireland agreed in June; from which departments; and how much was requested.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL1532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759563","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-20","<p>We want to see the financial support for Northern Ireland decided upon and spent by a devolved government to benefit the whole community. No funding has been allocated to date.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government receives regular representations from departments of the Northern Ireland Executive on a range of matters of importance to Northern Ireland and the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL1531 ; HL1532","2017-09-20T10:36:25.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759563/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759563/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which stakeholders they have consulted about the allocation of the £1 billion additional funding for Northern Ireland agreed in June.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL1533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759564","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-25","<p>Public grants to heritage railways may be permitted under state aid rules provided they meet the eligibility and other criteria set out in Chapter 1 and Articles 53 and 54 of the General Block Exemption Regulation 651/2014. It was under this legislation that the English Aid for Cultural and Heritage Conservation State Aid scheme was notified to the European Commission.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-09-25T13:03:36.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759564/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759564/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-12","Cultural Heritage: Transport","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether public grants to heritage railways and tramways are permitted under state aid rules where they fall within the English Aid for Cultural and Heritage Conservation State Aid Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Faulkner of Worcester",,"Lord Faulkner of Worcester","HL1534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759565","Home Office","false","2017-09-22","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes data on the number of arrests broken down by offence group and police force area. These data are published in the ‘Police Powers and Procedures, England and Wales’ statistical bulletins, and data can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016</a></p><p>Data presented here are on the police power of arrest. In line with police recorded crime statistics, these data cover arrests for all notifiable offences carried out by police in England and Wales</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-09-22T12:36:32.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759565/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759565/answer","police-powers-procedures-hosb1516.pdf","Police Powers and Procedures - Stats bulletin 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759565/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-12","Aviation: Lasers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many people have been arrested on suspicion of endangering an aircraft with a laser pointer under the Aviation and Safety Act 1982 within the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lord Fink",,"Lord Fink","HL1535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759566","Home Office","false","2017-09-20","<p>Potential victims of modern slavery in England and Wales are entitled to a reflection and recovery period for a minimum of 45 calendar days, or until a conclusive decision has been made on their victim status. This meets and exceeds obligations under the European Convention on Action against Trafficking in Human Beings, which requires a minimum of 30 days of support. In practice, many potential victims are in support for more than 90 days.</p><p>As part of the Government’s reform of the National Referral Mechanism, we are working with partners to assess how the current system works in practice and consider the support we provide to victims, to ensure that it enables them to begin to recover, rebuild their lives, and avoid future exploitation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-09-20T14:11:01.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759566/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759566/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-12","Slavery: Victims","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of how the 45 day reflection and recovery period for victims of trafficking and modern slavery, under the National Referral Mechanism, is working in practice; and whether that time limit is 45 working days, or 45 calendar days.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759567","Home Office","false","2017-09-20","<p>The review into the funding of Islamist extremist activity in the UK used the Government’s definition of extremism, set out in the Counter-Extremism Strategy published in October 2015. Extremism is the vocal or active opposition to our fundamental values, including democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty and the mutual respect and tolerance of different faiths and beliefs. We also regard calls for the death of members of our armed forces as extremist.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-09-20T14:12:38.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759567/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759567/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-12","Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 12 July (HLWS40), what definition of political and social extremism they used in the Home Office Review; and whether that definition included religious conservatism.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759568","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>The UK Government regularly raises with the Government of Israel concerns about the situation for Palestinians in East Jerusalem, the West Bank and Gaza, and pushes for an easing of restrictions. We are firmly committed to the promotion and protection of human rights, and call upon all parties to abide by International Humanitarian Law. Ultimately peace will only come through fresh negotiations between the parties, which the UK fully supports, and it is critical that Israel and the Palestinians take advantage of any momentum gathered through international efforts.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T16:00:19.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759568/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759568/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will propose measures to improve the status quo for the people of East Jerusalem, the West Bank and Gaza, for humanitarian reasons and to prepare the way for permanent peace negotiations.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759569","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-27","<p>This was not discussed on 5 September. We have seen no evidence to suggest there has been any funding of Daesh by the Government of Saudi Arabia. Where we do have concerns we do not shy away from raising them. Saudi Arabia has had its own painful experiences as the victim of numerous Daesh attacks. It is a key ally in the fight against Daesh, participating in coalition airstrikes to fight it and speaking out against its poisonous ideology.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-27T15:10:06.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759569/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759569/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Saudi Arabia: Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they made to the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Saudi Arabia, Abdel al-Jubeir, when he visited London on 4 September, concerning reports of financial and logistical support provided by Saudi Arabia to Daesh and other radical Sunni groups in the Middle East and Asia.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL1539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759570","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-27","<p>Saudi Arabia remains a Foreign and Commonwealth Office human rights priority country, particularly because of the restrictions on freedom of religion or belief. Although not discussed on 5 September, we regularly raise our concern with the Government of Saudi Arabia.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-27T15:09:49.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759570/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759570/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Saudi Arabia: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they made to the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Saudi Arabia, Abdel al-Jubeir, when he visited London on 4 September, concerning religious freedom, eliminating discriminatory enforcement of laws against religious minorities, and promoting respect and tolerance for minority Muslim and non-Muslim religious practices and beliefs.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL1540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759571","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>Saudi Arabia remains a human rights priority country because of the restrictions on the freedom of religion and belief, including the prohibition on publicly practising religions other than Islam. The UK Government strongly supports the right to freedom of religion or belief as set out in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and subsequent international human rights instruments.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T16:00:38.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759571/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759571/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Saudi Arabia: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of freedom of religion or belief in Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL1541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759572","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-27","<p>During his visit to London on 4-5 September, Saudi Foreign Minister Adel al-Jubeir had meetings with the Prime Minister and Foreign Secretary. Both raised the importance of Coalition compliance with their international humanitarian law obligations.</p><p>The UK Government takes its arms export licensing responsibilities very seriously and operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world. Our defence exports to Saudi Arabia are kept under careful and continual review to ensure they meet the rigorous standards of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. All export licence applications are assessed on a case-by-case basis, taking account of all relevant factors at the time of the application.</p><p>We welcomed the High Court’s ruling in July this year that UK Government decisions on arms export licensing to Saudi Arabia are lawful. The judgment stated the Government was rationally entitled to conclude that Saudi Arabia has been, and remains, genuinely committed to compliance with international humanitarian law. We note the application to appeal and will continue to defend the decisions challenged.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-27T16:03:32.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759572/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759572/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what guarantees, if any, they sought from the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Saudi Arabia, Abdel al-Jubeir, when he visited London on 4 September, that British arms sales to Saudi Arabia will only be used in accordance with international humanitarian law.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL1542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759573","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Green Paper consultation set out our ambition to transform employment prospects for disabled people and people with long-term health conditions, and sought views on a range of issues including how to improve occupational health provision, drawing lessons from the Fit for Work service. We have been carefully considering the responses we received, to inform our approach to better supporting individuals to stay in and return to work. We will set out our plans for taking forward our ambitions in the Autumn.</p><p> </p><p>We would like to take this opportunity to thank Lord Luce and the Chronic Pain Policy Coalition for their response to the Green Paper consultation which has given us valuable insight.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-09-19T15:54:08.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759573/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759573/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Fit for Work Programme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they expect to reach conclusions following their review of the Fit for Work Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL1543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759574","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-25","<p>The recent change in the Valuation Office Agency’s approach to assessing single business spaces covering multiple floors follows a Supreme Court judgement. The Government is considering the implications of this judgement, and any potential impact on small and medium-sized businesses. Following Budget 2016, the Government announced a wide-ranging package of measures to support rate payers, that will be worth £9 billion over the next five years.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-09-25T13:00:07.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759574/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759574/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-12","Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much revenue they expect to receive in the next financial year from the tax on single business spaces covering multiple floors, as set out by the Valuation Office Agency; and what is their estimate of the average cost to each small and medium-sized enterprise affected by that change.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL1544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759575","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-20","<p>At around 5.5m, small and medium-sized businesses comprise 99.9% of UK businesses. The Government recognises the importance of small and medium-sized businesses and the valuable contribution that they make to our economy.</p><p>To avoid overburdening businesses the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 has, amongst other things, reduced regulatory burdens, improved payment practices across the public sector and improved access to finance.</p><p>In many instances it would be difficult to quantify the monetary benefit directly attributable to the support provided under the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015, rather than by other business activities.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-09-20T10:17:56.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759575/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759575/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-12","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the monetary benefit to individual small and medium-sized enterprises from support provided under the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL1545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759576","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-22","<p>Royal Fleet Auxiliary (RFA) MOUNTS BAY is currently carrying the following equipment while conducting humanitarian assistance and disaster relief in the Caribbean:</p><p> </p><p>1 Wildcat helicopter</p><p>1 Mexflote raft</p><p>1 Combat support boat</p><p>2 Pacific 24 rigid inflatable boats</p><p>2 Inflatable raiding crafts</p><p>2 Medium wheeled tractors</p><p>2 Support Vehicles (15 tonne)</p><p>1 Rough terrain forklift</p><p>1 Light wheeled tractor</p><p>2 Quad bikes with trailers</p><p>2 Pinzgauer soft top all-terrain vehicles</p><p>1 Self loading dump truck</p><p>2 Bandvagn 206D flatbeds</p><p>1 Support Vehicle (six tonne)</p><p>1 Land Rover &amp; trailer</p><p>1 King Trailer</p><p> </p><p>This amounts to one helicopter, four tractors, zero bulldozers, 15 other vehicles and three items of heavy lifting equipment.</p><p> </p><p>HMS OCEAN is also due to arrive in the region by 23 September with three Wildcat, four Merlin and two Chinook helicopters and 60 tonnes of Department for International Development supplies onboard to assist with the longer-term recovery effort. HMS OCEAN will be deployed according to need once Hurricane Maria has passed.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-09-22T12:22:37.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759576/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759576/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-12","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the complement of disaster relief equipment carried by Royal Fleet Auxiliary Mount Bay; and in particular, how many (1) helicopters, (2) tractors, (3) bulldozers, (4) other vehicles, and (5) items of heavy lifting equipment are being carried.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL1546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759577","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-26","<p>On 6 September 2017 RAF Brize Norton was notified of the potential requirement to provide humanitarian relief flights and on 7 September the station was tasked to prepare those flights.</p><p> </p><p>Having identified and prioritised the relief stores required and established which runways remained open following Hurricane Irma's impact, the first aircraft were loaded and dispatched from RAF Brize Norton on 8 September, reaching the Caribbean that night.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence is providing significant support to the relief efforts in the Caribbean following the devastation caused by Hurricane Irma. Royal Fleet Auxiliary (RFA) MOUNTS BAY was pre-positioned in the region and loaded with aid precisely so we could respond to hurricane damage. So far 60 tonnes of much needed humanitarian aid has been distributed across the region by air. HMS OCEAN arrived in the British Virgin Islands on Friday 22 September with a further 60 tonnes of aid and is helping to deliver humanitarian assistance and disaster relief and engineering tasks.</p><p> </p><p>UK military personnel will continue to provide immediate support after Hurricane Maria has passed. Defence activity will remain under constant review and we will continue to work with local authorities to establish what is required.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL1548","2017-09-26T12:41:12.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759577/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759577/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-12","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when relief aircraft at RAF Brize Norton were ordered to be loaded up to fly to the disaster zone affected by Hurricane Irma.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL1547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759578","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-26","<p>On 6 September 2017 RAF Brize Norton was notified of the potential requirement to provide humanitarian relief flights and on 7 September the station was tasked to prepare those flights.</p><p> </p><p>Having identified and prioritised the relief stores required and established which runways remained open following Hurricane Irma's impact, the first aircraft were loaded and dispatched from RAF Brize Norton on 8 September, reaching the Caribbean that night.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence is providing significant support to the relief efforts in the Caribbean following the devastation caused by Hurricane Irma. Royal Fleet Auxiliary (RFA) MOUNTS BAY was pre-positioned in the region and loaded with aid precisely so we could respond to hurricane damage. So far 60 tonnes of much needed humanitarian aid has been distributed across the region by air. HMS OCEAN arrived in the British Virgin Islands on Friday 22 September with a further 60 tonnes of aid and is helping to deliver humanitarian assistance and disaster relief and engineering tasks.</p><p> </p><p>UK military personnel will continue to provide immediate support after Hurricane Maria has passed. Defence activity will remain under constant review and we will continue to work with local authorities to establish what is required.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL1547","2017-09-26T12:41:12.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759578/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759578/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-12","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when RAF Brize Norton was informed of the impact of Hurricane Irma and of the need for relief flights.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL1548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759579","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is the lead Department for responding to crises overseas, including natural disasters. The Met Office, as the UK’s National Meteorological Service, monitors weather around the world, including hurricanes in the Caribbean, and provides the FCO and other departments with up to date meteorological advice. This ensures coordinated and timely cross government preparations and response.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-10T12:53:27.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759579/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759579/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which department is responsible for overseeing weather phenomena during the Caribbean hurricane season.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL1549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759580","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-21","<p>DFID is liaising urgently with governments in the region to understand their needs for medical staff. We are also working with the Department of Health, and Public Health England to carry out needs assessments and UK medical experts are standing by to deploy as required and if requested by local governments.</p><p> </p><p>DFID has already offered up to £2.5 million to the Pan American Health Organisation, which is supporting them to provide health services including deployment of medical staff to the region.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to do all it can to support those affected.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-09-21T12:04:19.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759580/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759580/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-12","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many medical doctors they have sent to assist in the disaster zone affected by Hurricane Irma; when those doctors left the UK; and where they went.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL1550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759581","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Met Office is the UK National Met Service and monitors weather around the world, including hurricanes in the Caribbean such as Irma. For this purpose the Met Office uses a wide range of observations, including satellite and remote sensing technologies which form a crucial input to its weather modeling capability. Model predictions on the track of hurricanes together with information on their intensity and structure are used by the Met Office in its briefings to Her Majesty’s Government but also shared with the American National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) National Hurricane Centre.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-09-19T13:05:03.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759581/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759581/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-12","Hurricanes and Tornadoes: Caribbean","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether use was made of the UK's remote sensing and satellite technology to predict the impact of the storm system of Hurricane Irma; and if so, by whom.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL1551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759582","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>The Foreign Secretary met the Iranian Foreign Minister on 18 September and raised the cases of our British/Iranian dual-national detainees, including Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe. I also raised our dual national detainees with the Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister, at the UN General Assembly in New York.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL1553","2017-09-26T16:00:53.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759582/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759582/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Foreign Secretary intends to meet the Iranian Foreign Minister or members of his team at the next UN General Assembly; and if so, whether he will seek to ensure that the British Ambassador to Iran can visit the detained British-Iranian citizen Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe, particularly in the light of concerns about her health.","false","Biography information for Baroness Northover",,"Baroness Northover","HL1552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759583","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>The Foreign Secretary met the Iranian Foreign Minister on 18 September and raised the cases of our British/Iranian dual-national detainees, including Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe. I also raised our dual national detainees with the Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister, at the UN General Assembly in New York.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL1552","2017-09-26T16:00:53.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759583/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759583/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to make an appeal to Iran to release Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe, in the context of the theme of the General Debate of the 72nd Session of the UN General Assembly, Focusing on people: striving for peace and a decent life for all on a sustainable planet.","false","Biography information for Baroness Northover",,"Baroness Northover","HL1553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759584","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>We are not aware of any request to assist on this matter from either the legal representative or family of Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe, but we will consider what assistance we may be able to offer should a request be made.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T15:56:55.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759584/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759584/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how they are taking forward the request from Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe's legal representative that an independent medical commission should examine her for her fitness to remain in prison; and whether they intend to seek assurances that any such assessment will be objective.","false","Biography information for Baroness Northover",,"Baroness Northover","HL1554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759585","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-18","<p>The government established an independent Financial Policy Committee (FPC) and gave the FPC a primary objective to identify, monitor and take action to remove or reduce systemic risks with a view to protecting and enhancing financial stability. The FPC’s June 2017 Financial Stability Report (FSR), assesses recent trends in the consumer credit market, including dealership car finance and personal contract purchase (PCP) agreements. The FSR notes that PCP agreements have been growing rapidly, from around three-fifths of new car purchases financed through dealership car finance in 2011 to four-fifths in 2016, but that arrear rates on dealership car finance are generally lower that other forms of consumer credit.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-09-18T11:55:19.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759585/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759585/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Cars: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the number of personal contract purchase plans taken out to finance car purchases over each of the last five years; and what assessment they have made of the potential impact of such loans on (1) the car industry, and (2) the UK economy, if there were to be a widespread failure to repay such loans.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759586","Department of Health","false","2017-09-20","<p>With the support of the Department and the Chief Medical Officer, Public Health England (PHE) has established a national cross-agency expert group, the National Strategic Group on Viral Hepatitis, to provide strategic direction and advice around all types of viral hepatitis, including hepatitis C. It will provide advice to PHE, the Department, NHS England and to the wider health system. The new group is committed to working towards the World Health Organization goal to eliminate viral hepatitis as a major public health threat and brings together partner organisations to improve health services, minimise the number of new infections and reduce the health consequences of viral hepatitis for people in England. A priority is addressing the cross-system operational barriers in case finding and treatment capacity.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-09-20T13:22:49.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759586/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759586/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-12","Hepatitis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have established the cross-agency expert group on viral hepatitis to provide strategic direction and advice around hepatitis C and other viral hepatitis, as announced in March.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759587","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-18","<p>The Government is considering the findings of the independent Hendry Review before deciding, in light of the relevant factors, its position on the proposed Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon project.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-09-18T11:53:08.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759587/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759587/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-12","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their timescale for making a decision on plans for a Swansea tidal lagoon, following publication of the Hendry Review in January.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759588","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-26","<p>Hitachi Rail and Great Western Railway (GWR) are testing the Intercity Express Trains in diesel and electric to ensure they can deliver existing timetables and offer journey time reductions once electrification is complete. We remain confident that journey time improvements will be delivered. Testing is ongoing in the run up to the Intercity Express Train introduction on the GWR network.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-09-26T15:48:14.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759588/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759588/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Trains: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what comparative assessment they have made of (1) new Intercity Express bi-mode trains, and (2) fully electric trains, in respect of their (a) acceleration, and (b) overall speed.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759589","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-26","<p>The Government has set out its ambition for almost all cars and vans to be zero emissions by 2050, and that sales of new conventional cars and vans will end by 2040. By setting these long-term goals, the Government can ensure that there is plenty of time to ready the grid for the mass transition towards cleaner, more efficient vehicles.</p><p>We have regular discussions with all the key parties in the electricity systems – including energy suppliers, network operators and National Grid – to ensure that all parties are prepared for electric vehicle take up. The capacity market is our principal tool for ensuring we have sufficient capacity to meet demand. National Grid use the latest trends in supply and demand (including from electric vehicles) when advising on the volume of capacity to secure through these auctions.</p><p>Distribution Network Operators forecast the likely uptake of plug-in electric vehicles, in discussion with Government, in order to shape their investment plans. Government is also taking powers as part of the Automated and Electric Vehicles Bill to require all new chargepoints sold or installed in the UK to be smart enabled. Smart charging can help reduce the impact of electric vehicles on the electricity network by ensuring that they can flex to the grid’s need, avoiding existing peaks in demand.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-09-26T15:56:10.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759589/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759589/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-12","Electric Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to improve the capacity of the electricity grid to cope with additional demand resulting from increased numbers of electric cars and buses.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759590","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>There are no current plans to establish a new body to investigate serious incidents involving public transport on the roads as there are well-established collision investigation units within the police service and effective ways in place to report the conclusions and outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>The department currently supports the police STATS-19 collision reporting system and directly funds a programme of detailed investigation under the Road Accident in-depth Study in conjunction with police forces, coroners and several hospitals.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-09-20T13:01:43.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759590/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759590/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Public Transport: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to establish an impartial body to investigate serious incidents involving public transport on the roads, similar to the services provided in relation to rail by the Rail Accident Investigation Branch and the Office of Road and Rail.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759591","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-25","<p>The Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) has stated that safety at the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE) sites is acceptable. The ONR's decision to place the AWE Aldermaston site under enhanced regulatory attention was due to issues relating principally to ageing facilities, which do not pose any immediate safety concerns.</p><p>AWE has a plan in place for the long-term safe management of radioactive waste and this has resulted in the successful closure of the ONR's Improvement Notice regarding this matter.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence works closely with AWE, monitoring all aspects of its performance, including regulatory compliance.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-09-25T14:35:44.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759591/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759591/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-12","AWE Aldermaston","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government why the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE) Aldermaston has been placed on special measures for the fourth year running; whether the AWE has produced a plan for dealing with high levels of radioactive waste; if not, why not; and whether they have made an assessment of the extent to which any failure to do so puts staff and residents in the area surrounding that establishment at risk.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759592","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-21","<p>In 2015-16 DFID direct bilateral expenditure on reproductive health care, including training of personnel, was nearly £65 million. This excludes direct bilateral expenditure on family planning, which is reported separately. On HIV/AIDS prevention, treatment and care direct bilateral expenditure was £27m.</p><p>This data uses the specific reproductive health and HIV input sector codes set by the OECD/DAC. This does not capture spend on related programming that complements our wider work on HIV and reproductive health (for example family planning services, maternal and neo-natal health, strengthening health systems, research activities and our substantial contribution to the Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria).</p><p>Data for all sector codes are available on the Statistics for International Development website. Data for 2016/17 will be released early in 2018.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL1563","2017-09-21T12:08:22.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759592/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759592/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-12","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much bilateral expenditure was directly targeted by DFID towards HIV and AIDS in (1) 2015-16, and (2) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759593","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-21","<p>In 2015-16 DFID direct bilateral expenditure on reproductive health care, including training of personnel, was nearly £65 million. This excludes direct bilateral expenditure on family planning, which is reported separately. On HIV/AIDS prevention, treatment and care direct bilateral expenditure was £27m.</p><p>This data uses the specific reproductive health and HIV input sector codes set by the OECD/DAC. This does not capture spend on related programming that complements our wider work on HIV and reproductive health (for example family planning services, maternal and neo-natal health, strengthening health systems, research activities and our substantial contribution to the Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria).</p><p>Data for all sector codes are available on the Statistics for International Development website. Data for 2016/17 will be released early in 2018.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL1562","2017-09-21T12:08:22.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759593/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759593/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-12","Developing Countries: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much bilateral expenditure was directly targeted by DFID towards reproductive health in (1) 2015–16, and (2) 2016–17.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759594","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>​While we have not made any assessment of this issue, we have been clear that we believe that a durable ceasefire agreement should ensure that Hamas and other terrorist groups permanently end rocket fire and other terrorist attacks against Israel, and that all terrorist groups in Gaza should disarm. Our policy on Hamas remains clear: Hamas must renounce violence, recognise Israel and accept previously signed agreements. Hamas must make credible movement towards these conditions, which remain the benchmark against which its intentions should be judged. We call on those in the region with influence over Hamas to encourage them to take these steps.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T15:59:56.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759594/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759594/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Israel: Gaza","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports that Hamas leaders have offered the government of Israel a long-term ceasefire in exchange for the blockade on the Gaza Strip being lifted.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759595","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>The Minister of State for the Middle East issued a statement on 6 September condemning the eviction of the Shamanseh family from the property they have lived in for decades in East Jerusalem. The UK considers such evictions contrary to international law and they cause unnecessary suffering. The increased trajectory of evictions, demolitions and settlements in East Jerusalem undermines the prospects for peace.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T15:59:42.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759595/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759595/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding reports of the eviction of families living in East Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759596","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>We have not made representations on this issue. Under the EU arms embargo to Myanmar, the UK would not export military equipment to Israel if we believed that the ultimate end user destination would be Burma.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T15:57:56.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759596/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759596/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Israel: Burma","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports that the government of Israel has supplied weapons to the government of Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759597","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-26","<p>The Government stands up for and strongly supports the right of freedom of expression. We have concerns about the contraction of space for free speech in the Occupied Palestinian Territories. Our Consul-General to Jerusalem raised our concerns over the arrest and detention of human rights activists and advocates of free speech with the Palestinian Authority on 10 September.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-26T15:58:11.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759597/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759597/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Palestinians: Freedom of Expression","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the Palestinian Authority following reports of restrictions being imposed on free speech and the arrest of activists who have criticised Palestinian Authority leaders.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759598","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-25","<p>The Transport Community Treaty was signed by Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) on 19 September 2017. The Government actively supported EU-led efforts to encourage Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) to sign up to the Treaty. The Treaty is an important step to improve infrastructure and transport links in BiH and the Western Balkan region.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-09-25T14:37:31.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759598/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759598/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-12","Bosnia and Herzegovina: Transport Community Treaty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to encourage the signing of the Transport Community Treaty by Bosnia and Herzegovina.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Tankerness",,"Lord Wallace of Tankerness","HL1568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759602","Attorney General","false","2017-09-26","<p>The information requested is containing in the following tables, broken down into the different Law Officers' Departments.</p><p><strong>SFO</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Individuals leaving the SFO under exit schemes since 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total payment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>£281k</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>£324k</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Attorney General’s Office (AGO), the Government Legal Department (GLD) and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Individuals leaving the AGO, GLD and HMCPSI under exit schemes since 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total payment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>Fewer than 5</p></td><td><p>£172,148</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>Fewer than 5</p></td><td><p>£317,933</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Since 31 March 2016, there have been 5 or fewer men and 5 or fewer women who have left the Attorney General’s Office (AGO), the Government Legal Department (GLD) and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI) under an early exit scheme.</p><p><strong>CPS</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Individuals leaving the CPS under exit schemes since 31 March 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total payment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>£1,024,651</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>£500,040</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-26T12:38:27.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759602/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759602/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-12","Attorney General: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left the Law Officers' Departments under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759604","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>Details of the number, type, compensation levels and cost of exits from my Department<br>are routinely published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts. These are<br>available on the Cabinet Office website at<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office- annual-reports- and-accounts .</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T15:02:56.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759604/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759604/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Cabinet Office: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759605","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The majority of electoral registration activity is funded by local authorities across England,<br>Scotland and Wales. Since 2014 the Cabinet Office has provided funding to LAs to cover<br>the additional costs generated by the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration,<br>including a second bidding round after the canvass if initial funding is insufficient to cover<br>costs incurred over the year.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:32:18.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759605/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759605/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electoral Registration Officers: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding for electoral registration officers.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759606","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The most recent formal assessment of register quality, based on the 1 December 2015 registers<br>and published in July 2016, found that individual electoral registration boosted the accuracy of the<br>register by 4 per cent</p><p>Alongside individual registration, the successful introduction of online registration has transformed<br>the way citizens can register. It now takes just a few minutes to apply to register and nearly 30<br>million citizens have taken the opportunity to do so in the last three years. In large part thanks to<br>online registration, the parliamentary register used for the 2017 general election was the largest<br>ever at nearly 47 million</p><p>2.9 million applications were submitted between the calling of the election and the registration<br>deadline date, with 622,000 applications coming on deadline day itself</p><p>The government has continued to modernise the registration process and to make it more<br>accessible, as underscored, for example by recent policy commitments on making it easier for<br>survivors of domestic abuse to register anonymously.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-20T14:54:41.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759606/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759606/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the UK voter registration system.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759607","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>There are no more recent audited figures than those published in the answer of 15<br>December 2016 to Question 57073, GOV.UK Verify has cost £54.4m to develop and has<br>saved £111.44m.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-19T12:17:59.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759607/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759607/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 57073, what the cost to the public purse of the gov.uk Verify system has been to date.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759608","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>Guidance on the roles and responsibilities of tellers is already produced by the Electoral<br>Commission. Tellers must also act in accordance with any further guidance provided by<br>the relevant Returning Officer or their staff. There are currently no plans to put such<br>guidance on a statutory footing.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:51:08.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759608/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759608/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Returning Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he has plans to bring forward legislative proposals to codify the roles and responsibilities of tellers at polling stations.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759609","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Government intends to publish a democratic engagement strategy addressing<br>registration issues in late 2017.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:47:57.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759609/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759609/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the timetable is to bring forward proposals on the registration of people in (i) universities, (ii) colleges, (iii) residential care homes and (iv) houses in multiple occupation.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759610","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Cabinet Office is committed to finding an appropriate approach to reducing the burden of duplicate applications while ensuring that unnecessary barriers to registration are avoided. The fact that millions of people have taken the step of applying to register online shows it was right to introduce the website as part of Individual Electoral Registration.</p><p>We have already taken steps to limit unnecessary duplicate applications to register. For example during the recent general election we added a new page to the website to guide people away from making applications when they did not need to.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:45:55.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759610/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759610/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electoral Register: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the timetable is to bring forward proposals to tackle duplicate voter registrations.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759611","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-20","<p>There are no immediate plans to do so. The process for serving election Writs is set out in the Representation of the People Act 1983. However, the Government continues to work with the Law Commissions, as well as other stakeholders such as the Electoral Commission, to streamline the electoral process.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-20T15:47:27.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759611/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759611/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-12","Elections: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of an electronic system for the delivery, receipt and return of the Writ at UK parliamentary elections.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759612","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>Electoral Returning Officers (EROs) already have wide powers to access data to improve<br>the quality of the register. The Cabinet Office is working with administrators and their<br>representatives and the Electoral Commission to investigate additional potential use of<br>data to aid EROs in their registration duties.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-20T14:39:16.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759612/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759612/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electoral Register: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the timetable is to bring forward proposals to improve data-sharing in the voter registration process.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759613","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>Sir Eric Pickles’ review of Electoral Fraud, published in August 2016, recommended<br>introducing an attestation requirement for postal vote applications requiring a signature<br>waiver</p><p>The Government supports this recommendation and will be seeking to consider, in<br>conjunction with the Association of Electoral Administrators and the Electoral Commission,<br>how this might be implemented in due course.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:52:30.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759613/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759613/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing an attestation arrangement for postal vote applications requiring a signature waiver.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759614","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>We consider elections processes and policy on an ongoing basis, and are working with the<br>Association of Electoral Administrators and Electoral Commission to consider the<br>development and improvement of existing processes, including in relation to the<br>procedures for the counting of votes at elections.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:57:22.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759614/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759614/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Ballot Papers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of removing the absolute requirement to count unused ballot papers as a part of the verification process and replacing that requirement with a requirement to do so only where the returning officer considers it appropriate.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759615","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p><strong>Combining polls can bring benefits in terms of enhancing voter participation and reducing cost. However, it is recognised that changing the rules surrounding the combination of polls would be a complex exercise involving amendments to primary legislation. We will continue to consider this matter with stakeholders to see where improvements can be made.</strong></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:53:34.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759615/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759615/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Ballots","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will conduct a review of the combination of polls which includes an assessment of (a) which polls should be automatically combined, (b) the maximum number of polls that should be combined on the same day and (c) the potential merits of combining polls for parish and community councils and neighbouring planning and council tax referendums with UK Parliamentary general elections.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759616","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>Returning Officers have six months in which to submit an account of spending on a poll<br>funded from the Consolidated Fund. The vast majority of these claims are received by the<br>ECU in the last month before the deadline. This raises an issue with processing the<br>claims, many of which require significant work, within six months of receipt, including how<br>quickly queries on a claim are responded to by Returning Officers</p><p>We are looking at the process with the Association of Electoral Administrators to identify<br>how it may best be operated.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:33:46.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759616/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759616/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Elections: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that expenses claims submitted to the Election Claims Unit are audited and settled within six months of their receipt.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759617","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Government keeps elections processes and policy under review and Cabinet Office<br>officials are actively discussing timetables and other processes with the Association of<br>Electoral Administrators and the Electoral Commission to understand the issues and<br>identify practicable solutions that put electors first.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-20T14:40:39.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759617/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759617/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will conduct a review of all election and electoral registration deadlines which includes the consideration of deadlines for the registration of electors, overseas electors and absent voting.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759618","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>We will continue to work with the Law Commission, as well as other stakeholders such as the Electoral Commission, on how best to implement the recommendations of its review of electoral law.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:56:53.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759618/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759618/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Law Commissioners proposals of February 2016, on reforming electoral laws, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals for a single Electoral Administration Act.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759619","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>We consider that the current arrangements, whereby local authorities are responsible for<br>designating polling places and carrying out reviews, ensure that there is a clear and<br>consistent approach, and clear lines of accountability, in the designation of polling districts<br>and places. There are no plans to change these existing arrangements.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:46:47.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759619/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759619/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of giving (a) electoral registration officers the responsibility for the subdivision of UK parliamentary constituencies into polling districts and (b) returning officers the responsibility for the designation of polling places within those districts.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759620","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The current boundary review is proceeding in accordance with legislation passed in the<br>2010-15 Parliament under which the four Boundary Commissions are required to submit<br>their final reports in September 2018</p><p>These reforms will ensure fair and equal representation for the voting public across the<br>United Kingdom.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:49:58.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759620/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759620/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government plans to end the Boundary Commission's review of constituency boundaries.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759621","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>Electronic counting is used in only a small number of polls. However, in considering<br>whether to extend the use of electronic counting, we would need to take into account the<br>cost, accuracy and integrity of adopting it more widely. In previous polls electronic counting<br>has been more expensive and has not been as quick as expected in some circumstances</p><p>We therefore currently have no plans to further its use.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-20T14:44:58.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759621/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759621/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-12","Elections: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the effectiveness of the (a) current use of electronic forms of electoral counting and (b) potential merits of introducing such electronic forms of counting for other types of elections.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759622","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-20","<p>DCMS is not taking any steps to ensure that online travel agents do not charge commission on the full VAT inclusive bill for bookings taken online.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-09-20T13:02:01.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759622/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759622/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-12","Travel Agents: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that online travel agents do not charge commission on the full VAT inclusive bill for bookings taken online.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","10272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759623","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-20","<p>DCMS has not conducted an assessment of the effect of online travel agents charging commission on the full VAT inclusive bill for bookings taken online on hospitality SMEs in rural and deprived areas.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-09-20T13:04:27.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759623/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759623/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-12","Travel Agents: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of online travel agents charging commission on the full VAT inclusive bill for bookings taken online on hospitality SMEs in rural and deprived areas.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","10273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759624","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-15","<p>The Government concluded a fundamental review of business rates at Budget 2016 with a package of reductions worth almost £9bn over the next five years. As a next step the Government aims to revalue properties more frequently and to look more broadly at the way in which we address the perceived unfairness that companies that operate in bricks and mortar are effectively treated differently from companies that do not. The Government will provide an update in due course.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-15T13:57:00.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759624/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759624/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to announce the results of the Government's review into business rates.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","10276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759625","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market, transferring regulatory responsibility from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) in April 2014. This more robust regulatory system is helping to deliver the Government’s vision for a well-functioning and sustainable consumer credit market which is able to meet consumers’ needs. Treasury ministers and officials meet regularly with the FCA to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold the requested estimate, but the FCA’s rules require firms to reasonably expect that in at least 51% of credit agreements entered into as a result of a promotion, credit will be provided to the consumer at the representative APR or lower. The FCA’s rules also require firms to ensure that their communications and financial promotions are fair, clear and not misleading. The FCA is able to impose tough sanctions, such as banning products, imposing unlimited fines and ordering firms to pay money back to customers, where wrongdoing is found.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","10193","2017-10-09T13:12:31.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759625/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759625/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Loans: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have had loans approved at the advertised representative APR rates for loan products.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","10192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759626","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market, transferring regulatory responsibility from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) in April 2014. This more robust regulatory system is helping to deliver the Government’s vision for a well-functioning and sustainable consumer credit market which is able to meet consumers’ needs. Treasury ministers and officials meet regularly with the FCA to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold the requested estimate, but the FCA’s rules require firms to reasonably expect that in at least 51% of credit agreements entered into as a result of a promotion, credit will be provided to the consumer at the representative APR or lower. The FCA’s rules also require firms to ensure that their communications and financial promotions are fair, clear and not misleading. The FCA is able to impose tough sanctions, such as banning products, imposing unlimited fines and ordering firms to pay money back to customers, where wrongdoing is found.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","10192","2017-10-09T13:12:31.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759626/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759626/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Loans: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Financial Conduct Authority on the number of customers offered loans at a higher rate than that advertised by UK financial institutions.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","10193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759627","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>In the last 12 months we have named 592 employers for non-payment of the National Minimum Wage. The name and location of these employers is recorded within press notices, which can be found on <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/record-number-of-employers-named-and-shamed-for-underpaying" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/record-number-of-employers-named-and-shamed-for-underpaying</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/record-2-million-back-pay-identified-for-13000-of-the-uks-lowest-paid-workers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/record-2-million-back-pay-identified-for-13000-of-the-uks-lowest-paid-workers</a></p><p>Geographic information of employers prosecuted for non-compliance with the National Minimum Wage is published in the Government’s 2017 evidence to the Low Pay Commission on compliance and enforcement: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-minimum-wage-government-evidence-to-the-low-pay-commission-on-compliance-and-enforcement-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-minimum-wage-government-evidence-to-the-low-pay-commission-on-compliance-and-enforcement-2017</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-09T16:36:39.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759627/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759627/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-12","Minimum Wage: Non-payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many companies in each region have been (a) named and shamed and (b) prosecuted for non-payment of the minimum wage in each of last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","10167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759628","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>In the Written Ministerial Statement on 13 July, the Government made clear that only businesses with a turnover above the VAT threshold (currently £85,000) will be mandated to use Making Tax Digital from April 2019, and then only to meet their VAT obligations. The Government also confirmed that Making Tax Digital will not be widened before it has been shown to work well, and then not before April 2020 at the earliest.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T12:59:32.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759628/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759628/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Taxation: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on (a) administration processes and (b) tax take of increasing the making tax digital threshold applicable from 2020 to the level of the personal allowance.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759629","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The eligibility criteria for free software under the Making Tax Digital proposals is set out in Annex C of the document covering the relationship between HMRC and software developers. The document can be found at : <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/making-tax-digital-software-suppliers-terms-of-collaboration/terms-of-collaboration-between-hm-revenue-and-customs-and-software-developers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/making-tax-digital-software-suppliers-terms-of-collaboration/terms-of-collaboration-between-hm-revenue-and-customs-and-software-developers</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T13:05:12.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759629/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759629/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Taxation: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9026, on taxation: electronic government, what the eligibility criteria will be to establish which businesses will be entitled to free software in order to meet their income tax obligations as part of the Making Tax Digital pilot phase.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759630","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-19","<p>Treasury ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sector as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p>Regulation of consumer credit, including credit cards, is the responsibility of the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The FCA conducted a credit card market study in November 2014 and published its final report in July 2016. Following this, it consulted in April 2017 on proposed remedies to tackle persistent debt in the credit card market. The government will continue to work with the FCA to ensure that customers are treated fairly<strong>.</strong></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-19T10:55:58.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759630/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759630/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Credit Cards: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received on the practice of credit card lenders targeting individuals who have unaffordable levels of debt.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","10027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759631","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Data from UK Finance shows that the number of UK homes bought as buy-to-let between January and June 2016 was 63,800, and the number of UK homes bought as buy-to-let between January and June 2017 was 36,300.</p><p> </p><p>A significant increase in buy-to-let transaction volumes occurred in March 2016. This preceded changes to Stamp Duty Land Tax, which introduced a 3% surcharge on purchases of Buy-to-Let properties.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-09T13:09:17.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759631/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759631/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of homes bought as buy to let in January to June (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","10056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759632","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-20","<p>The Government has received £3,356.3m from the Mineworkers’ Pension Scheme and £3,119m from the British Coal Staff Superannuation Scheme since 1994.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-20T09:01:42.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759632/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759632/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Mining: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has received from the Mineworkers Pension Scheme and the British Coal Staff Superannuation Scheme since 1994.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","10313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759633","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-15","<p>Until 2015, surpluses for each scheme were shared equally between scheme members and the Government as Guarantor. That arrangement continues for the MPS but new arrangements were agreed in 2015 for the BCSSS. How the members’ share of the surplus is used is a matter for the Trustees</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-15T13:56:15.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759633/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759633/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-12","Mining: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the additional benefits that have been awarded under surplus sharing arrangements to members of the (a) the Mineworkers Pension Scheme and (b) British Coal Staff Superannuation since 1994.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","10310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759634","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-19","<p>Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) enforce the National Minimum Wage on behalf of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS). In 2016/17, HMRC identified £10.9m of underpayments, owed to 98,000 workers. The enforcement budget has been increased to £25.3m for 2017/18.</p><p>Effective communications are an integral part of our strategy for promoting compliance. Both BEIS and HMRC provide information and guidance to help employers ensure they are compliant, and we encourage Local Authorities and other agencies to use these resources and others to support employer compliance.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-19T08:54:24.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759634/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759634/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-12","Local Government: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support local authorities to tackle non-compliance with the National Minimum Wage.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","10031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759635","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>We are unable to provide this information as to do so would be at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-09T10:20:28.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759635/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759635/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-12","Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will place in the Library copies of all correspondence between his Department and (a) local authorities, (b) the Local Government Association and (c) London councils in the last three years relating to residential fire safety.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","10066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759636","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>Data for DCLG covers annual pay remit years for all staff eligible for a pay award. This does not include pay adjustments on promotion or new appointees not eligible for a pay award.</p><p>Pay remits, which are drawn up in accordance with HMT guidelines to reflect an average 1 per cent spend, are signed off by the Secretary of State for delegated grades AO – G6. Pay awards for SCS staff are made in accordance with SSRB guidelines, overseen by the Cabinet Office</p><p>Data for 2014/15 includes contractual buy-out payments made in excess of 1 per cent as part of the Department’s pay reform exercise to move people off guaranteed pay progression.</p><p>It was agreed as part of the second phase of Pay Reform in 2015/16 that additional contractual obligations could be funded outside of the 1 per cent. Salary increases below 1 per cent include part consolidated pay awards where the person was less than 1 per cent from the maximum of the pay range. In 2015/16 very few employees on legacy terms were due contractual milestones, so funds could be targeted at those on the new reformed terms, giving them slightly above the 1 per cent.</p><p>Data for 2016/17 shows a limited number of staff receiving more than 1 per cent which includes uplifts to the new minima of pay ranges where these were increased by more than 1 per cent; and it includes transitional arrangements for Administrative Officers with adjustments greater than 1 per cent It also includes the SCS pay awards ranging from 0.7 per cent up to 2.3 per cent, in accordance with the SSRB guidelines, with an overall spend of 1 per cent of SCS paybill.</p><p>Salary increases shown do not include contractual milestones to those few employees who remain on legacy terms.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2014/15</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2015/16</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Salary Increases</p></td><td><p>Median Salary Increase</p></td><td><p>Number of Salary Increases</p></td><td><p>Median Salary Increase</p></td><td><p>Number of Salary Increases</p></td><td><p>Median Salary Increase</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less Than 1 %</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>0.83%</p></td><td><p>276</p></td><td><p>0.53%</p></td><td><p>1158</p></td><td><p>0.94%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Equal To 1%</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>1.00%</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>1.00%</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>1.00%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Than 1%</p></td><td><p>1122</p></td><td><p>1.50%</p></td><td><p>869</p></td><td><p>1.16%</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>1.94%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grand Total</p></td><td><p>1152</p></td><td><p>1.50%</p></td><td><p>1151</p></td><td><p>1.16%</p></td><td><p>1218</p></td><td><p>0.94%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-09T15:46:46.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759636/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759636/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-12","Department for Communities and Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above, (b) at and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10111"
